1
00:00:00,700 --> 00:00:01,700
CHAPTER ONE

2
00:00:01,700 --> 00:00:08,570
The city heat

3
00:00:08,570 --> 00:00:16,400
'When we get to Polreath on Saturday, I'm
going to do nothing,' said Anna.

4
00:00:16,400 --> 00:00:22,470
'I just want to sit and have cool drinks and
read and watch the world go by.'

5
00:00:22,470 --> 00:00:26,100
'Me too,' replied Stephen.

6
00:00:26,100 --> 00:00:29,580
It was the hottest summer for twenty years.

7
00:00:29,580 --> 00:00:32,960
It had started at the end of May.

8
00:00:32,960 --> 00:00:38,579
Everyone thought the heat would only last
for a few days and then the rain would return,

9
00:00:38,579 --> 00:00:40,590
but this summer was different.

10
00:00:40,590 --> 00:00:45,730
'And don't expect any intelligent conversation
from me,' Anna continued.

11
00:00:45,730 --> 00:00:51,670
'It'll take a day or two for me to become
a member of the human race again!'

12
00:00:51,670 --> 00:00:55,470
'Mm,' said Stephen, not really listening.

13
00:00:55,470 --> 00:01:01,390
'What about this cottage we've booked, do
you think it's going to be all right?

14
00:01:01,390 --> 00:01:07,280
To be honest, I'm a bit worried about it - we
were so late making our decision and it was

15
00:01:07,280 --> 00:01:09,080
still available.

16
00:01:09,080 --> 00:01:11,159
Why didn't anyone else want it?

17
00:01:11,159 --> 00:01:14,500
It makes me think there must be something
wrong with it.'

18
00:01:14,500 --> 00:01:16,390
'Don't worry.

19
00:01:16,390 --> 00:01:18,240
I'm sure it'll be fine.

20
00:01:18,240 --> 00:01:22,790
And even if it's not, we'll still be away
from here.

21
00:01:22,790 --> 00:01:27,240
Just think - three weeks by the sea, without
any work.

22
00:01:27,240 --> 00:01:30,390
It sounds wonderful.'

23
00:01:30,390 --> 00:01:33,990
In the city, the heat was uncomfortable.

24
00:01:33,990 --> 00:01:37,470
People were not used to high temperatures
day after day.

25
00:01:37,470 --> 00:01:43,780
Journeys to work became hot and sweaty, and
increasingly bad-tempered in the crowded trains

26
00:01:43,780 --> 00:01:45,850
and buses.

27
00:01:45,850 --> 00:01:51,320
By the beginning of July, nobody could remember
when it had last rained.

28
00:01:51,320 --> 00:01:57,009
Everywhere you looked seemed to be brown - the
grass in the parks was burnt and most of the

29
00:01:57,009 --> 00:01:59,310
flowers had died.

30
00:01:59,310 --> 00:02:05,469
The sun was burning hot and the air seemed
to be getting thicker and thicker.

31
00:02:05,469 --> 00:02:10,170
At the weekends, the place was empty as many
people left for the countryside.

32
00:02:10,170 --> 00:02:18,220
But Stephen and Anna couldn't leave - not
until the weekend anyway.

33
00:02:18,220 --> 00:02:22,700
Stephen was thirty-two with dark, curly hair.

34
00:02:22,700 --> 00:02:28,030
He had noticed a few grey hairs that morning
when he was drying it after his shower.

35
00:02:28,030 --> 00:02:33,970
But he didn't mind too much; in fact, he rather
liked the idea of a few which might make him

36
00:02:33,970 --> 00:02:35,810
look serious.

37
00:02:35,810 --> 00:02:40,379
But his face showed signs of stress and worry.

38
00:02:40,379 --> 00:02:43,519
Stephen left the flat just before seven.

39
00:02:43,519 --> 00:02:48,840
He was earlier than usual this morning because
he wanted to avoid the rush hour, but it seemed

40
00:02:48,840 --> 00:02:54,450
as if everyone else had had the same idea
- the roads were busy and there had been an

41
00:02:54,450 --> 00:02:58,500
accident half way along Sussex Gardens.

42
00:02:58,500 --> 00:03:03,830
He waited impatiently while the police sorted
out the chaos but by the time he arrived at

43
00:03:03,830 --> 00:03:07,870
work, he was late and not in a very good mood.

44
00:03:07,870 --> 00:03:13,390
He locked the Saab and went into the cool
building.

45
00:03:13,390 --> 00:03:18,810
The offices of Jardine and Makepeace, advertising
agents, were on the fourteenth floor of a

46
00:03:18,810 --> 00:03:23,670
modern block with wonderful views over Regent's
Park.

47
00:03:23,670 --> 00:03:29,140
But this morning, when Stephen found himself
climbing the stairs (the lift was out of order

48
00:03:29,140 --> 00:03:36,000
again!), he would happily have given up the
views for an office on the ground floor.

49
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:40,920
'Please let everything go smoothly today,'
he said to himself as he made his way up the

50
00:03:40,920 --> 00:03:43,470
stairs.

51
00:03:43,470 --> 00:03:49,640
Stephen was worried about work - the agency
had lost an important client that week.

52
00:03:49,640 --> 00:03:54,989
He felt that Charlie Jardine, the agency boss,
blamed him.

53
00:03:54,989 --> 00:04:01,220
A couple of days before, he'd passed by Charlie's
office and had heard him saying on the phone,

54
00:04:01,220 --> 00:04:05,069
'Yes, well, I'll have to talk to Stephen about
that.

55
00:04:05,069 --> 00:04:08,930
He was the one working on their new advertisement.'

56
00:04:08,930 --> 00:04:15,140
Stephen hadn't heard any more but he thought
that Charlie sounded a bit angry.

57
00:04:15,140 --> 00:04:20,280
He wondered if it was a bad time to go on
holiday - perhaps his job would disappear

58
00:04:20,280 --> 00:04:22,490
when he was away.

59
00:04:22,490 --> 00:04:28,330
But he didn't want to miss this break - and
in any case, Anna would kill him if he suggested

60
00:04:28,330 --> 00:04:30,000
cancelling.

61
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:32,720
So he said nothing to her about his worries.

62
00:04:32,720 --> 00:04:38,260
He often found it hard to talk about his problems,
even with Anna.

63
00:04:38,260 --> 00:04:41,039
God knows why, she was usually willing to
listen.

64
00:04:41,039 --> 00:04:48,560
In his mind, he would think through different
ways of opening the conversation with her,

65
00:04:48,560 --> 00:04:55,590
but everything he thought of sounded so obvious
- 'I'm worried about work' or 'I'd like to

66
00:04:55,590 --> 00:04:58,100
talk to you about something'.

67
00:04:58,100 --> 00:05:02,770
In any case, he really preferred to work things
out himself.

68
00:05:02,770 --> 00:05:07,580
But he knew he was not easy to live with when
he didn't talk much.

69
00:05:07,580 --> 00:05:10,850
'Morning Mark.

70
00:05:10,850 --> 00:05:15,800
Another lovely day,' panted Stephen, and sat
down to get his breath back.

71
00:05:15,800 --> 00:05:19,259
His shirt was wet and sticking to his back.

72
00:05:19,259 --> 00:05:21,740
'Morning Stephen,' said Mark.

73
00:05:21,740 --> 00:05:24,729
'I'm not sure if it is a lovely day.

74
00:05:24,729 --> 00:05:30,220
Clare's away - she's got food poisoning or
something - so between us we've got to do

75
00:05:30,220 --> 00:05:32,449
her work as well as our own.'

76
00:05:32,449 --> 00:05:34,120
'Oh hell!

77
00:05:34,120 --> 00:05:37,860
Just what I needed to hear!' replied Stephen.

78
00:05:37,860 --> 00:05:42,000
Anna's last day began even earlier.

79
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:47,639
At 6.30 that morning, she yawned as she walked
across to St Phillips Hospital.

80
00:05:47,639 --> 00:05:52,919
It was another beautiful morning - for her
the best time of the day when the air was

81
00:05:52,919 --> 00:05:56,650
still fresh and the day was still full of
promise.

82
00:05:56,650 --> 00:06:02,100
Her nurse's cap sat comfortably on her short
blond hair.

83
00:06:02,100 --> 00:06:05,620
She looked fresh and efficient in her blue
uniform.

84
00:06:05,620 --> 00:06:09,639
She loved her job as a nurse but it was hard.

85
00:06:09,639 --> 00:06:15,910
There always seemed to be so much to do - more
than ever since the new manager had arrived.

86
00:06:15,910 --> 00:06:21,920
'This weekend, when we're away,' she thought,
'I'm going to get up early and walk along

87
00:06:21,920 --> 00:06:25,790
the beach before anyone else is awake.'

88
00:06:25,790 --> 00:06:29,660
Then she laughed at the idea of getting up
early when she didn't have to!

89
00:06:29,660 --> 00:06:36,560
Well, maybe she would - who knows, holidays
can change people.

90
00:06:36,560 --> 00:06:40,160
Maybe that's what she needed - change.

91
00:06:40,160 --> 00:06:44,689
She was thirty and had been working at St
Phillips since she'd finished her training

92
00:06:44,689 --> 00:06:48,090
- perhaps it was time to move on.

93
00:06:48,090 --> 00:06:54,250
Later in the day, she went to say goodbye
to Michael Barton, a favourite patient who

94
00:06:54,250 --> 00:06:56,639
was recovering from a major operation.

95
00:06:56,639 --> 00:07:00,310
'Have a wonderful holiday!' he said.

96
00:07:00,310 --> 00:07:01,879
'Thanks, I will.

97
00:07:01,879 --> 00:07:07,500
And I hope I won't see you when I get back,'
replied Anna.

98
00:07:07,500 --> 00:07:11,680
And as soon as she said it, she realised what
a stupid thing it was to say.

99
00:07:11,680 --> 00:07:18,200
'I mean, I hope you won't still be in hospital,
you know, you'll be back at home,' she said

100
00:07:18,200 --> 00:07:19,200
quickly.

101
00:07:19,200 --> 00:07:20,990
'It's all right, love.

102
00:07:20,990 --> 00:07:24,370
I know you weren't talking about me dying!

103
00:07:24,370 --> 00:07:29,889
I hope I don't see you either - although I'll
miss you looking after me.

104
00:07:29,889 --> 00:07:33,550
Bye - all the best.'

105
00:07:33,550 --> 00:07:38,960
She left the ward knowing that this time tomorrow
she would be in a different world.

106
00:07:38,960 --> 00:07:43,940
She got off the hospital bus at the end of
her street and walked slowly home, thinking

107
00:07:43,940 --> 00:07:47,270
about a cool beer in the back garden.

108
00:07:47,270 --> 00:07:48,710
They were lucky.

109
00:07:48,710 --> 00:07:55,350
Their flat was on the ground floor of a nineteenth-century
house and the garden at the back was theirs.

110
00:07:55,350 --> 00:08:01,330
The garden wasn't big but it was a wonderful
place to escape to in the summer.

111
00:08:01,330 --> 00:08:04,820
She wondered what sort of day Stephen had
had.

112
00:08:04,820 --> 00:08:09,990
She knew something was worrying him but was
too tired to do anything about it.

113
00:08:09,990 --> 00:08:15,289
Anyway, she knew from past experience that
it was no use asking directly.

114
00:08:15,289 --> 00:08:20,780
He'd once told her that he could only talk
about difficult things after they were past

115
00:08:20,780 --> 00:08:23,539
and no longer difficult.

116
00:08:23,539 --> 00:08:26,729
'I'll find out what it is on holiday,' she
thought.

117
00:08:26,729 --> 00:08:31,500
'When we've got more time and energy.'

118
00:08:31,500 --> 00:08:36,470
As Stephen was about to leave the office that
evening, Charlie Jardine called him into his

119
00:08:36,470 --> 00:08:41,410
office and told him that there were going
to be some changes in the next month, that

120
00:08:41,410 --> 00:08:46,870
probably one member of staff would have to
go - 'be made redundant' was how Charlie said

121
00:08:46,870 --> 00:08:55,740
it, but Stephen thought 'sacked... fired...
dismissed' was what he really wanted to say.

122
00:08:55,740 --> 00:09:01,460
Then Charlie said, 'But of course, I don't
want to lose you.'

123
00:09:01,460 --> 00:09:04,019
Why didn't that make Stephen feel better?

124
00:09:04,019 --> 00:09:13,589
He left work with a heavy heart.

125
00:09:13,589 --> 00:09:15,200
CHAPTER TWO

126
00:09:15,200 --> 00:09:16,200
On the way

127
00:09:16,200 --> 00:09:19,560
'Got everything?'

128
00:09:19,560 --> 00:09:20,560
asked Anna.

129
00:09:20,560 --> 00:09:23,590
'I don't care if we haven't!' said Stephen.

130
00:09:23,590 --> 00:09:24,870
'Let's go!

131
00:09:24,870 --> 00:09:26,420
You drive.'

132
00:09:26,420 --> 00:09:27,589
'OK.

133
00:09:27,589 --> 00:09:32,560
We've got to stop at Rebecca's to leave our
keys with her,' said Anna, shutting the front

134
00:09:32,560 --> 00:09:34,120
door quietly behind her.

135
00:09:34,120 --> 00:09:38,360
'She said she'd come in and make sure everything
is OK while we're away.

136
00:09:38,360 --> 00:09:39,360
Remember?

137
00:09:39,360 --> 00:09:44,560
Oh, and did you write down our holiday address
for her - she said she wanted it in case of

138
00:09:44,560 --> 00:09:45,560
emergencies.

139
00:09:45,560 --> 00:09:49,010
Though I don't think I want to know if there
are any emergencies, do you?

140
00:09:49,010 --> 00:09:53,019
Now where did I put the car keys?'

141
00:09:53,019 --> 00:09:57,589
'You always think you've lost the keys, and
you never have,' said Stephen.

142
00:09:57,589 --> 00:10:00,480
'I think you just say it to annoy me.

143
00:10:00,480 --> 00:10:02,800
Get in and drive!

144
00:10:02,800 --> 00:10:07,750
I've got the address for Rebecca, I've got
the map, I've got the address of the cottage

145
00:10:07,750 --> 00:10:11,279
and you've got enough bottles of suntan cream
to protect an army.

146
00:10:11,279 --> 00:10:12,750
Now, come on!

147
00:10:12,750 --> 00:10:15,950
We're wasting valuable holiday time!'

148
00:10:15,950 --> 00:10:17,160
'Right.

149
00:10:17,160 --> 00:10:18,329
I'll drive first.

150
00:10:18,329 --> 00:10:20,580
Why don't you go to sleep?

151
00:10:20,580 --> 00:10:25,140
I'll wake you when it's your turn to drive,'
said Anna.

152
00:10:25,140 --> 00:10:29,050
London looked a bit like a ghost town at seven
o'clock that Saturday morning.

153
00:10:29,050 --> 00:10:34,649
Either everybody had left it for their own
holidays or they were still in bed.

154
00:10:34,649 --> 00:10:40,750
It was good to leave the city behind as Anna
set off west along the M4 on the 500 kilometre

155
00:10:40,750 --> 00:10:42,800
drive to Polreath.

156
00:10:42,800 --> 00:10:49,080
Polreath was a small, quiet fishing village
on the north-west coast of Cornwall with a

157
00:10:49,080 --> 00:10:55,480
few holiday cottages, two hotels, and the
usual shops, bars and restaurants.

158
00:10:55,480 --> 00:11:01,180
It was famous for its seafood restaurants
- lobsters, prawns, crabs - and relatively

159
00:11:01,180 --> 00:11:05,540
unspoilt - a great place to relax.

160
00:11:05,540 --> 00:11:09,480
It would take most of the day to get there
but Anna was happy to drive.

161
00:11:09,480 --> 00:11:15,820
It gave her time to think about last night
when Stephen had come home from work.

162
00:11:15,820 --> 00:11:20,950
He had looked almost ill - he said it was
only the heat and the traffic, and he just

163
00:11:20,950 --> 00:11:23,130
needed some peace and quiet.

164
00:11:23,130 --> 00:11:28,191
He had gone into the garden with a bottle
of beer and walked around looking as if he

165
00:11:28,191 --> 00:11:33,000
was interested in the flowers (which she knew
he wasn't).

166
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:37,769
She had left him alone and after a while,
he came in for dinner, seeming a bit more

167
00:11:37,769 --> 00:11:38,769
cheerful.

168
00:11:38,769 --> 00:11:44,269
They had had a perfectly pleasant evening
talking about arrangements for the next day

169
00:11:44,269 --> 00:11:47,149
and had gone to bed without mentioning work.

170
00:11:47,149 --> 00:11:52,930
But later, she had woken up and heard him
in the kitchen, talking to someone on the

171
00:11:52,930 --> 00:11:55,070
telephone.

172
00:11:55,070 --> 00:11:59,960
When he had come back to bed, she had pretended
to be asleep.

173
00:11:59,960 --> 00:12:02,769
In the morning, neither of them had mentioned
it.

174
00:12:02,769 --> 00:12:10,560
'Oh well, when we've both relaxed, perhaps
he'll talk about it,' thought Anna.

175
00:12:10,560 --> 00:12:15,579
The sun was behind her and she could feel
its warmth on her shoulders.

176
00:12:15,579 --> 00:12:21,019
There wasn't much traffic about so she put
her foot down, and as the kilometres passed,

177
00:12:21,019 --> 00:12:26,050
she felt her head begin to clear of all the
worries, the questions.

178
00:12:26,050 --> 00:12:32,310
She put a cassette on quietly - a little Mozart
for company, perfect - and started to enjoy

179
00:12:32,310 --> 00:12:33,310
the drive.

180
00:12:33,310 --> 00:12:37,670
'Where are we?' asked Stephen sleepily.

181
00:12:37,670 --> 00:12:42,550
'We've just passed Bristol, so I suppose we're
doing well,' said Anna.

182
00:12:42,550 --> 00:12:45,240
'Your turn to drive.'

183
00:12:45,240 --> 00:12:46,620
'OK.

184
00:12:46,620 --> 00:12:50,899
Let's stop and have a cup of coffee first.'

185
00:12:50,899 --> 00:12:55,850
Anna turned into the next service area where
they had to queue for a fairly awful cup of

186
00:12:55,850 --> 00:12:57,980
coffee.

187
00:12:57,980 --> 00:13:02,820
Half an hour later, they were back on the
road, this time with Stephen driving.

188
00:13:02,820 --> 00:13:08,220
He changed the music to an Ella Fitzgerald
tape and Anna attempted to sing along with

189
00:13:08,220 --> 00:13:09,220
her.

190
00:13:09,220 --> 00:13:15,699
'I think I prefer Ella Fitzgerald to you,
if you don't mind,' joked Stephen.

191
00:13:15,699 --> 00:13:19,899
'Sorry, this song always makes me want to
sing,' replied Anna.

192
00:13:19,899 --> 00:13:24,190
'Don't worry, I'll go to sleep in a minute.'

193
00:13:24,190 --> 00:13:26,029
Stephen turned off the motorway.

194
00:13:26,029 --> 00:13:31,040
He reckoned it would take about another three
hours to get to Polreath.

195
00:13:31,040 --> 00:13:32,360
Anna was asleep.

196
00:13:32,360 --> 00:13:38,600
'She wasn't last night, though, when I came
back to bed after that phone call, I know.

197
00:13:38,600 --> 00:13:40,680
She's not very good at pretending.'

198
00:13:40,680 --> 00:13:42,760
Stephen looked at her lovingly.

199
00:13:42,760 --> 00:13:47,990
'Perhaps it was a mistake to ring Mark, but
I wanted to tell him what Charlie had said

200
00:13:47,990 --> 00:13:50,730
about making someone redundant.

201
00:13:50,730 --> 00:13:53,500
Now all I've done is make Mark feel bad, too.

202
00:13:53,500 --> 00:13:55,180
I must be going mad.

203
00:13:55,180 --> 00:13:57,540
Why did I tell him?

204
00:13:57,540 --> 00:14:02,079
He'll find out soon enough if he's going to
lose his job.'

205
00:14:02,079 --> 00:14:03,850
Anna moved beside him.

206
00:14:03,850 --> 00:14:08,910
'Not long now,' said Stephen, trying to forget
about work.

207
00:14:08,910 --> 00:14:13,720
'I'll be really happy to get out of this hot
car, won't you?'

208
00:14:13,720 --> 00:14:14,720
'Mmm.'

209
00:14:14,720 --> 00:14:17,290
'First thing I'm going to do is have a swim,'
he said.

210
00:14:17,290 --> 00:14:23,339
'What about unpacking the car, and buying
a few things like milk and bread for tomorrow's

211
00:14:23,339 --> 00:14:24,339
breakfast?' said Anna.

212
00:14:24,339 --> 00:14:26,260
'To hell with that.

213
00:14:26,260 --> 00:14:31,550
We're on holiday and we're going to do what
we want to do, not what we should.

214
00:14:31,550 --> 00:14:36,360
No more planning, no more thinking ahead,
no more worrying.'

215
00:14:36,360 --> 00:14:38,970
'I'll remember you said that.

216
00:14:38,970 --> 00:14:47,980
This sounds as if it's going to be an interesting
three weeks.'

217
00:14:47,980 --> 00:14:48,980
CHAPTER THREE

218
00:14:48,980 --> 00:14:52,550
Polreath

219
00:14:52,550 --> 00:14:56,030
Their first view of Polreath was from the
top of a hill.

220
00:14:56,030 --> 00:14:57,410
'Oh look, Stephen!

221
00:14:57,410 --> 00:14:58,709
The sea!

222
00:14:58,709 --> 00:15:02,370
And lots of little boats.

223
00:15:02,370 --> 00:15:06,399
It looks wonderful,' said Anna.

224
00:15:06,399 --> 00:15:12,069
There was a big sign at the side of the road-telling
motorists not to drive into the village, that

225
00:15:12,069 --> 00:15:14,639
they must leave their cars in the car park.

226
00:15:14,639 --> 00:15:15,639
'Right.

227
00:15:15,639 --> 00:15:19,060
Let's leave everything here.

228
00:15:19,060 --> 00:15:21,699
I'm going for a swim,' said Stephen.

229
00:15:21,699 --> 00:15:25,620
'Me too,' replied Anna.

230
00:15:25,620 --> 00:15:31,560
They walked hand in hand down the steep, narrow
street to the beach below.

231
00:15:31,560 --> 00:15:37,910
The water wasn't wonderfully warm - this was
the Atlantic after all - but even so that

232
00:15:37,910 --> 00:15:41,800
first swim was almost magical.

233
00:15:41,800 --> 00:15:48,509
Stephen lay on his back, looking at the sky
and enjoying the first taste of freedom.

234
00:15:48,509 --> 00:15:54,220
Anna had swum quite a long way out but was
now coming up towards him.

235
00:15:54,220 --> 00:15:58,639
He turned towards her and they managed a salty
kiss.

236
00:15:58,639 --> 00:16:01,339
'Hello, love.

237
00:16:01,339 --> 00:16:04,480
Welcome to our new world,' said Anna softly.

238
00:16:04,480 --> 00:16:07,910
'Hi, little one,' he said.

239
00:16:07,910 --> 00:16:10,589
'You look ten years younger already.

240
00:16:10,589 --> 00:16:14,590
And that's after only one swim!'

241
00:16:14,590 --> 00:16:17,000
They kissed again.

242
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:21,170
'Come on,' said Stephen, 'that's enough for
now.'

243
00:16:21,170 --> 00:16:25,019
'What, swimming or kissing?' asked Anna.

244
00:16:25,019 --> 00:16:30,200
'Both,' he smiled, and kissed her again.

245
00:16:30,200 --> 00:16:33,200
They swam slowly back to the beach.

246
00:16:33,200 --> 00:16:39,269
The sun still felt warm, so they sat on the
sand for a few minutes with their towels wrapped

247
00:16:39,269 --> 00:16:41,830
round them.

248
00:16:41,830 --> 00:16:47,949
Outside a pub, people were sitting with drinks
and watching them in a leisurely way.

249
00:16:47,949 --> 00:16:53,950
Anna and Stephen - the only ones on the beach
at that time suddenly realised that everyone's

250
00:16:53,950 --> 00:16:58,279
eyes were on them, so they picked up their
things and left.

251
00:16:58,279 --> 00:17:04,600
'We'd better go and introduce ourselves to
Mr Goddard and get the key for the cottage,'

252
00:17:04,600 --> 00:17:05,600
Stephen said.

253
00:17:05,600 --> 00:17:08,370
'He said to come to his house.

254
00:17:08,370 --> 00:17:10,789
What was it called, Anna?'

255
00:17:10,789 --> 00:17:12,260
'Seahorses,' she replied.

256
00:17:12,260 --> 00:17:15,100
'We passed it on the way down the hill.

257
00:17:15,100 --> 00:17:17,350
Look, you go.

258
00:17:17,350 --> 00:17:19,230
I want to change my clothes.

259
00:17:19,230 --> 00:17:26,230
'I don't know, one look at you in your swimsuit
and he might put the price down,' he replied.

260
00:17:26,230 --> 00:17:27,300
'Very funny!

261
00:17:27,300 --> 00:17:33,930
I'll wait on the corner over there,' she said,
giving him a little push.

262
00:17:33,930 --> 00:17:37,020
Anna watched as Stephen knocked on the door
of Seahorses.

263
00:17:37,020 --> 00:17:42,700
A youngish man appeared and she could hear
Stephen introduce himself.

264
00:17:42,700 --> 00:17:44,740
'Mr Goddard?

265
00:17:44,740 --> 00:17:47,390
Hello, I'm Stephen Martins.

266
00:17:47,390 --> 00:17:52,300
Sorry about my appearance but we got so hot
travelling down here that we had to have a

267
00:17:52,300 --> 00:17:54,270
quick swim,' he said.

268
00:17:54,270 --> 00:17:55,990
'No problem.

269
00:17:55,990 --> 00:17:57,980
I'm pleased you've arrived.

270
00:17:57,980 --> 00:18:00,200
I'm Tristan Goddard.

271
00:18:00,200 --> 00:18:01,830
Welcome.'

272
00:18:01,830 --> 00:18:06,840
He looked over Stephen's shoulder and saw
Anna standing at the corner.

273
00:18:06,840 --> 00:18:09,230
She gave a small wave and smiled.

274
00:18:09,230 --> 00:18:11,450
'That's Anna,' said Stephen.

275
00:18:11,450 --> 00:18:14,810
'She said she'd come and introduce herself
when she's changed.'

276
00:18:14,810 --> 00:18:16,980
'Fine.

277
00:18:16,980 --> 00:18:20,659
Well look, this is the key for Dolphin Cottage.

278
00:18:20,659 --> 00:18:26,860
Go down to the harbour, turn right and follow
that little road until you come to a stone

279
00:18:26,860 --> 00:18:27,860
cottage.

280
00:18:27,860 --> 00:18:30,730
You can't miss it, it's the only one with
a green door.'

281
00:18:30,730 --> 00:18:33,230
'Thanks.

282
00:18:33,230 --> 00:18:36,440
By the way, what about cars in the village?'

283
00:18:36,440 --> 00:18:37,570
Stephen asked.

284
00:18:37,570 --> 00:18:39,520
'Can I bring the car down?

285
00:18:39,520 --> 00:18:42,180
It's in the car park at the top of the hill
at the moment.'

286
00:18:42,180 --> 00:18:43,860
'Yeah,' replied Tristan.

287
00:18:43,860 --> 00:18:48,680
'You can bring it down to unpack everything,
but then you'll have to take it back up to

288
00:18:48,680 --> 00:18:49,710
the car park.

289
00:18:49,710 --> 00:18:53,540
We're trying to keep the village free of cars
as much as possible.

290
00:18:53,540 --> 00:18:57,630
It used to be a real problem with the fishermen
trying to get up and down to the harbour in

291
00:18:57,630 --> 00:19:01,160
their vans, and visitors parking on the streets.

292
00:19:01,160 --> 00:19:03,850
So now no visitors' cars are allowed.

293
00:19:03,850 --> 00:19:04,850
Sorry.'

294
00:19:04,850 --> 00:19:09,010
'That's OK,' Stephen said, 'I'll be perfectly
happy without it.'

295
00:19:09,010 --> 00:19:10,010
'Fine.

296
00:19:10,010 --> 00:19:16,540
I'll come down a bit later then to see that
everything's OK,' said Tristan.

297
00:19:16,540 --> 00:19:20,420
Tristan stood on the step and watched Stephen
join Anna.

298
00:19:20,420 --> 00:19:25,090
As they walked down the street holding hands,
he couldn't help noticing how good she looked

299
00:19:25,090 --> 00:19:27,020
in her swim suit.

300
00:19:27,020 --> 00:19:32,010
They seemed very comfortable with each other,
he thought, and wondered how long they'd been

301
00:19:32,010 --> 00:19:33,200
together.

302
00:19:33,200 --> 00:19:38,000
Half-smiling, he turned and went back into
the house, with the picture of Stephen and

303
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:40,130
Anna still in his head.

304
00:19:40,130 --> 00:19:46,860
Then the picture changed to him and Jill last
summer when they'd been so happy.

305
00:19:46,860 --> 00:19:53,220
Now she was in London and God knows when they
were going to be together again, if ever.

306
00:19:53,220 --> 00:19:59,490
She refused to live in Polreath - she said
it was 'too dead in the winter', and he knew

307
00:19:59,490 --> 00:20:01,840
he couldn't live in London.

308
00:20:01,840 --> 00:20:05,760
In fact, he had no wish to live anywhere but
Polreath.

309
00:20:05,760 --> 00:20:07,559
To him it had everything.

310
00:20:07,559 --> 00:20:13,510
For seven months of the year, the visitors
brought life and work to the village and for

311
00:20:13,510 --> 00:20:18,360
the remaining five months the locals had the
place to themselves.

312
00:20:18,360 --> 00:20:23,490
He loved it in the middle of winter when the
sea was rough and the waves crashed over the

313
00:20:23,490 --> 00:20:25,210
harbour wall.

314
00:20:25,210 --> 00:20:28,750
It was impossible then for any of the fishermen
to go to sea.

315
00:20:28,750 --> 00:20:35,179
And the village had the feeling of being an
island with no way of escape.

316
00:20:35,179 --> 00:20:41,720
Jill had wanted to leave as soon as the summer
had finished, to go back to the bright lights.

317
00:20:41,720 --> 00:20:46,860
This summer, she'd been down and for a few
weeks they'd got on as well together as last

318
00:20:46,860 --> 00:20:48,420
year.

319
00:20:48,420 --> 00:20:52,000
But soon he had seen that she was getting
bored.

320
00:20:52,000 --> 00:20:56,720
And then the telephone call with the promise
of a new, exciting job had pulled her back

321
00:20:56,720 --> 00:20:58,620
to London.

322
00:20:58,620 --> 00:21:06,170
They still spoke on the phone, but in his
heart, he knew that the whole thing was over.

323
00:21:06,170 --> 00:21:10,480
He sighed sadly and sat down to plan his work
for tomorrow.

324
00:21:10,480 --> 00:21:16,830
During the summer months, he took visitors
in his boat to Skellig - the island off the

325
00:21:16,830 --> 00:21:22,980
headland - on fishing trips and on daylong
trips along the coast, and anything else they

326
00:21:22,980 --> 00:21:25,169
wanted to do.

327
00:21:25,169 --> 00:21:29,590
And he still managed to do a bit of fishing
between trips.

328
00:21:29,590 --> 00:21:36,529
His first trip was at 9.30 - ten people to
take to Skellig.

329
00:21:36,529 --> 00:21:41,419
He left the front door open to get a bit more
air into the house and walked down the narrow

330
00:21:41,419 --> 00:21:44,289
streets to Dolphin Cottage.

331
00:21:44,289 --> 00:21:47,240
'Hello, anyone at home?'

332
00:21:47,240 --> 00:21:48,650
called Tristan.

333
00:21:48,650 --> 00:21:50,059
'Oh hello.

334
00:21:50,059 --> 00:21:51,250
I'm Anna.

335
00:21:51,250 --> 00:21:53,210
Come in.'

336
00:21:53,210 --> 00:21:55,900
Anna led the way into the kitchen.

337
00:21:55,900 --> 00:22:00,610
Tristan followed and thought she looked good
in jeans, too.

338
00:22:00,610 --> 00:22:02,679
Stephen was putting things away in cupboards.

339
00:22:02,679 --> 00:22:04,440
'Is everything OK?

340
00:22:04,440 --> 00:22:09,130
Have you found your way around?' asked Tristan.

341
00:22:09,130 --> 00:22:13,160
Stephen smiled, 'Yes, everything's just perfect.

342
00:22:13,160 --> 00:22:16,210
And thank you for buying the bread and milk
and things.

343
00:22:16,210 --> 00:22:18,500
How much do we owe you for that?'

344
00:22:18,500 --> 00:22:23,140
'Don't worry about it now, you can pay me
at the end.

345
00:22:23,140 --> 00:22:28,000
I thought you might arrive after the shop
had closed so I just bought a few essentials.'

346
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:32,950
'Thanks a lot,' said Anna.

347
00:22:32,950 --> 00:22:38,690
Stephen had told Anna that Tristan seemed
'very nice', and she had to agree.

348
00:22:38,690 --> 00:22:41,900
She found herself almost staring at him.

349
00:22:41,900 --> 00:22:49,529
He had the most amazing eyes - sort of strong
blue - that seemed to look through you.

350
00:22:49,529 --> 00:22:55,390
She thought he must be in his early thirties,
about the same age as Stephen, but taller

351
00:22:55,390 --> 00:22:59,850
and slimmer, and with those wonderful eyes!

352
00:22:59,850 --> 00:23:04,010
He was saying something to Stephen but she
wasn't really listening.

353
00:23:04,010 --> 00:23:05,700
'What do you think, Anna?

354
00:23:05,700 --> 00:23:08,150
Shall we go?' said Stephen.

355
00:23:08,150 --> 00:23:09,150
'What?

356
00:23:09,150 --> 00:23:11,460
Sorry, I wasn't listening.

357
00:23:11,460 --> 00:23:14,419
Shall we go where?'

358
00:23:14,419 --> 00:23:18,970
'Tristan was just saying that he was running
a boat trip to a little island at half past

359
00:23:18,970 --> 00:23:23,799
nine tomorrow morning and would we like to
go?' said Stephen.

360
00:23:23,799 --> 00:23:26,130
Anna said, 'Really?

361
00:23:26,130 --> 00:23:28,630
Do you often do boat trips?'

362
00:23:28,630 --> 00:23:31,450
'Yes, there's something happening every day.

363
00:23:31,450 --> 00:23:35,299
In fact, you should find a list of trips on
the wall by the back door.'

364
00:23:35,299 --> 00:23:40,020
Tristan pointed, 'Yes, look, there it is.'

365
00:23:40,020 --> 00:23:42,789
She made herself turn round to look.

366
00:23:42,789 --> 00:23:48,400
'I'd really quite like to explore Polreath
tomorrow morning,' Anna said.

367
00:23:48,400 --> 00:23:53,320
'It seems funny to go on a trip before we've
had a look round here first.

368
00:23:53,320 --> 00:23:55,420
We can go on the boat any day'

369
00:23:55,420 --> 00:23:56,420
'True.

370
00:23:56,420 --> 00:23:59,850
We'll do that then, Tristan,' said Stephen.

371
00:23:59,850 --> 00:24:05,590
'Have a day wandering around the village and
then come with you later in the week.'

372
00:24:05,590 --> 00:24:06,679
'OK.

373
00:24:06,679 --> 00:24:12,750
Well, I'll be off now and leave you to it,'
Tristan said, moving towards the door.

374
00:24:12,750 --> 00:24:16,100
'If you've got any problems, you know where
I live.

375
00:24:16,100 --> 00:24:18,090
Bye for now.'

376
00:24:18,090 --> 00:24:23,770
Half an hour later, Stephen and Anna were
sitting outside drinking coffee in the front

377
00:24:23,770 --> 00:24:25,300
garden.

378
00:24:25,300 --> 00:24:30,720
The cottage was exactly how they'd imagined
it - a traditional fisherman's cottage built

379
00:24:30,720 --> 00:24:35,100
of stone with very thick walls to keep out
the wind.

380
00:24:35,100 --> 00:24:38,200
The tiny garden at the front looked over the
harbour.

381
00:24:38,200 --> 00:24:41,309
'I can't believe our luck.

382
00:24:41,309 --> 00:24:46,370
Can you imagine anything more ideal than this?'
asked Anna.

383
00:24:46,370 --> 00:24:48,520
'And what about Tristan?

384
00:24:48,520 --> 00:24:51,610
Don't you think he's got the most amazing
eyes.

385
00:24:51,610 --> 00:24:54,190
I couldn't stop looking at him.'

386
00:24:54,190 --> 00:24:55,520
'I noticed!

387
00:24:55,520 --> 00:24:59,640
Actually, you're right, his eyes are interesting.

388
00:24:59,640 --> 00:25:02,000
I'd like eyes like that.'

389
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:07,120
'So would I. And I wouldn't mind his hair
either.

390
00:25:07,120 --> 00:25:14,289
It's all curly like yours is when you've just
had a shower, except his is really blond.'

391
00:25:14,289 --> 00:25:18,320
'OK, that's enough about Tristan,' laughed
Stephen.

392
00:25:18,320 --> 00:25:20,740
'I might get jealous.

393
00:25:20,740 --> 00:25:27,000
Anyway, he can't be so good-looking and a
really nice person - there's probably something

394
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:28,870
wrong with him!'

395
00:25:28,870 --> 00:25:35,460
Later, Stephen came into the bedroom drying
his hair after a cool shower.

396
00:25:35,460 --> 00:25:38,000
Anna looked at him and smiled.

397
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:42,670
She wondered if he remembered the conversation
about Tristan's hair.

398
00:25:42,670 --> 00:25:47,159
Had he come in with wet hair deliberately,
just to remind her that she'd always liked

399
00:25:47,159 --> 00:25:49,270
his hair?

400
00:25:49,270 --> 00:25:55,520
They lay there, side by side, touching, with
the sound of the sea coming through the open

401
00:25:55,520 --> 00:26:01,810
window.

402
00:26:01,810 --> 00:26:04,110
CHAPTER FOUR

403
00:26:04,110 --> 00:26:07,380
Exploring the village

404
00:26:07,380 --> 00:26:11,880
The next day, Anna woke up not long after
dawn.

405
00:26:11,880 --> 00:26:15,220
She could hear seagulls crying.

406
00:26:15,220 --> 00:26:18,549
She thought about an early morning walk.

407
00:26:18,549 --> 00:26:24,330
Maybe tomorrow, she decided, and turned over
for a bit more sleep.

408
00:26:24,330 --> 00:26:29,330
She didn't notice that Stephen wasn't lying
beside her.

409
00:26:29,330 --> 00:26:33,740
Stephen had woken up even earlier and had
heard the sounds of the birds.

410
00:26:33,740 --> 00:26:40,520
He lay there for a time, listening, but slowly
his mind started to fill up with memories

411
00:26:40,520 --> 00:26:43,309
of his last conversation with his boss.

412
00:26:43,309 --> 00:26:49,220
'Oh no,' he thought, 'I don't want to start
thinking about that now.

413
00:26:49,220 --> 00:26:53,720
I'm on holiday, I need a break.'

414
00:26:53,720 --> 00:26:58,400
But the problems of the last few weeks at
work wouldn't go away.

415
00:26:58,400 --> 00:27:03,570
He could feel his stomach begin to get tight
- a sure sign that he was getting worried.

416
00:27:03,570 --> 00:27:10,320
'It's no good,' he thought, 'I'll have to
get up and do something.'

417
00:27:10,320 --> 00:27:14,630
Quietly, he got dressed and left the cottage.

418
00:27:14,630 --> 00:27:19,720
The sun had just risen and the air already
felt warm.

419
00:27:19,720 --> 00:27:24,340
He started jogging up the hill out of the
village, hoping that some physical activity

420
00:27:24,340 --> 00:27:26,590
would help.

421
00:27:26,590 --> 00:27:30,260
By the time, he reached the top he was a bit
out of breath.

422
00:27:30,260 --> 00:27:37,510
He looked into the car park to make sure the
car was still there, then carried on walking.

423
00:27:37,510 --> 00:27:41,091
There was a signpost saying "Footpath" so
he went along it.

424
00:27:41,091 --> 00:27:45,340
It led to the edge of the cliff.

425
00:27:45,340 --> 00:27:50,909
At this point, he was standing about a hundred
metres above the sea, looking back down onto

426
00:27:50,909 --> 00:27:52,399
Polreath harbour.

427
00:27:52,399 --> 00:27:59,179
It was a wonderful view - one he felt he'd
always remember.

428
00:27:59,179 --> 00:28:04,330
There were one or two people on their boats
in the harbour, including a blond-haired man.

429
00:28:04,330 --> 00:28:09,740
'I wonder if that's Tristan,' thought Stephen.

430
00:28:09,740 --> 00:28:14,600
He watched the activity in the harbour and
slowly the tightness in his stomach started

431
00:28:14,600 --> 00:28:15,910
to go away.

432
00:28:15,910 --> 00:28:18,610
He felt calmer.

433
00:28:18,610 --> 00:28:23,840
He realised that the problems at work were
not going to disappear; he was going to have

434
00:28:23,840 --> 00:28:30,159
to think about his job clearly and carefully,
and decide what he really wanted to do.

435
00:28:30,159 --> 00:28:33,600
And try and talk to Anna about it.

436
00:28:33,600 --> 00:28:38,260
Once or twice recently, he had seen her looking
at him almost angrily.

437
00:28:38,260 --> 00:28:41,110
'Poor Anna,' he thought.

438
00:28:41,110 --> 00:28:43,740
'She must get fed up with me sometimes.'

439
00:28:43,740 --> 00:28:52,059
He had started to walk back along the path
when he heard voices from the harbour below.

440
00:28:52,059 --> 00:28:57,419
He turned and saw a dark-haired man standing
at the front of a fishing boat, shouting at

441
00:28:57,419 --> 00:28:59,350
the blond man.

442
00:28:59,350 --> 00:29:02,840
They seemed to be having some sort of argument.

443
00:29:02,840 --> 00:29:07,510
The dark-haired man kept pointing at the blond
man's boat.

444
00:29:07,510 --> 00:29:11,601
Stephen enjoyed the fact that other people
seemed to have problems at work, too, not

445
00:29:11,601 --> 00:29:13,650
just him!

446
00:29:13,650 --> 00:29:16,679
And he watched as the two small boats left
the harbour.

447
00:29:16,679 --> 00:29:23,340
When he got back to Dolphin Cottage with some
fresh bread, Anna was sitting in the front

448
00:29:23,340 --> 00:29:26,120
garden with a cup of coffee.

449
00:29:26,120 --> 00:29:31,540
She looked at him closely and said, 'Hello,
are you all right?'

450
00:29:31,540 --> 00:29:33,520
'Yes, I'm fine.

451
00:29:33,520 --> 00:29:38,779
I woke up early and decided to get some exercise...
and some fresh bread.

452
00:29:38,779 --> 00:29:42,059
Here, smell it, straight from the baker's.'

453
00:29:42,059 --> 00:29:44,059
'Mm, delicious.

454
00:29:44,059 --> 00:29:46,679
Let's have breakfast out here.

455
00:29:46,679 --> 00:29:50,370
You can tell me what the village is like.'

456
00:29:50,370 --> 00:29:54,840
Stephen told her about the argument in the
harbour, and how he was sure one of the men

457
00:29:54,840 --> 00:30:00,269
was Tristan, but he didn't tell her what had
made him get up so early.

458
00:30:00,269 --> 00:30:04,090
Time to get serious later, not now.

459
00:30:04,090 --> 00:30:10,010
Stephen and Anna spent the rest of the morning
wandering round the village.

460
00:30:10,010 --> 00:30:15,630
They walked up and down the narrow streets
and paths, looking at everything.

461
00:30:15,630 --> 00:30:21,390
Most of the houses near the harbour were like
theirs - old stone cottages.

462
00:30:21,390 --> 00:30:26,620
There were one or two which were obviously
holiday cottages but most of them still seemed

463
00:30:26,620 --> 00:30:29,550
to be lived in by local people.

464
00:30:29,550 --> 00:30:35,890
A bit further away from the harbour, it seemed
to be more mixed - some more modern houses

465
00:30:35,890 --> 00:30:41,370
and one or two very fine ones which had probably
been built when it had first become fashionable

466
00:30:41,370 --> 00:30:45,980
for city people to take their holidays by
the sea.

467
00:30:45,980 --> 00:30:53,309
In one of the small side streets, they found
Philpots, a restaurant specializing in seafood.

468
00:30:53,309 --> 00:30:58,260
The menu promised lobster, crab and fish,
all freshly caught.

469
00:30:58,260 --> 00:31:00,630
'This looks wonderful.'

470
00:31:00,630 --> 00:31:03,130
'And look at the prices!

471
00:31:03,130 --> 00:31:07,029
This lot would cost twice as much in London.'

472
00:31:07,029 --> 00:31:10,000
Stephen felt a hand on his shoulder.

473
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:11,010
'Morning.'

474
00:31:11,010 --> 00:31:14,710
Tristan was standing behind them in shorts
and a T-shirt.

475
00:31:14,710 --> 00:31:17,370
'You were up early today, Stephen.

476
00:31:17,370 --> 00:31:19,320
I saw you leaving the cottage.'

477
00:31:19,320 --> 00:31:22,919
'Yes, I went jogging,' replied Stephen.

478
00:31:22,919 --> 00:31:24,990
'I didn't see you, though.'

479
00:31:24,990 --> 00:31:29,649
'I was on the boat - just going out for an
hour or two's fishing,' said Tristan.

480
00:31:29,649 --> 00:31:34,860
'Ah, so it was him,' thought Stephen.

481
00:31:34,860 --> 00:31:37,639
'Did you catch anything?' he asked Tristan.

482
00:31:37,639 --> 00:31:40,539
'I just put down the lobster pots.

483
00:31:40,539 --> 00:31:42,429
I'll go back later and pull them up.

484
00:31:42,429 --> 00:31:46,490
I usually get a few and then sell them to
this place.

485
00:31:46,490 --> 00:31:51,519
So if you eat here tonight, they might be
serving my lobsters,' said Tristan, looking

486
00:31:51,519 --> 00:31:52,669
at Anna.

487
00:31:52,669 --> 00:31:54,830
'Great,' said Anna.

488
00:31:54,830 --> 00:31:57,410
'How was the trip to the island?'

489
00:31:57,410 --> 00:31:58,520
'Oh fine.

490
00:31:58,520 --> 00:32:01,800
I left the people there for the day.

491
00:32:01,800 --> 00:32:05,280
There's not much to do, but that's what's
attractive, I suppose.

492
00:32:05,280 --> 00:32:11,080
They just walk round, look at the few people
who actually live there and think how wonderful

493
00:32:11,080 --> 00:32:14,530
it'd be to have a house on a small island.

494
00:32:14,530 --> 00:32:18,779
They see it on a wonderful, sunny day like
today and don't think about the times in the

495
00:32:18,779 --> 00:32:22,460
winter when it's cut off for days by the storms.

496
00:32:22,460 --> 00:32:27,029
But it's a very special place and you need
to be a special kind of person to be able

497
00:32:27,029 --> 00:32:28,580
to enjoy it!'

498
00:32:28,580 --> 00:32:35,020
For some reason, Stephen felt Tristan was
that special kind of person - a man who would

499
00:32:35,020 --> 00:32:36,980
be happy with his own company.

500
00:32:36,980 --> 00:32:38,860
'Well, see you later.

501
00:32:38,860 --> 00:32:43,909
Have a good day,' said Tristan, and walked
off in the direction of the harbour.

502
00:32:43,909 --> 00:32:49,409
'Let's go and have lunch in that pub by the
beach, and plan the rest of the day,' said

503
00:32:49,409 --> 00:32:50,409
Anna.

504
00:32:50,409 --> 00:32:52,929
'OK,' replied Stephen.

505
00:32:52,929 --> 00:32:56,890
'Well, we now know two things about Tristan.

506
00:32:56,890 --> 00:33:02,340
One, not everybody here likes him - remember
I told you about that argument in the harbour

507
00:33:02,340 --> 00:33:08,760
this morning - and two, he seems to have strong
feelings about the island.'

508
00:33:08,760 --> 00:33:15,260
'And three, he's got nice legs!' said Anna
as she watched him climb onto his boat.

509
00:33:15,260 --> 00:33:16,260
'Anna!

510
00:33:16,260 --> 00:33:20,590
Can't you think of anything except his eyes
and legs?

511
00:33:20,590 --> 00:33:21,590
Honestly!

512
00:33:21,590 --> 00:33:25,669
And they say it's men who think about sex
all the time!'

513
00:33:25,669 --> 00:33:27,140
Stephen's voice sounded half-serious.

514
00:33:27,140 --> 00:33:30,680
Actually, he was a bit surprised.

515
00:33:30,680 --> 00:33:35,669
He'd never known Anna talk so openly about
a man's physical appearance.

516
00:33:35,669 --> 00:33:38,559
He didn't quire know whether to be worried
about it.

517
00:33:38,559 --> 00:33:41,149
'Its all right.

518
00:33:41,149 --> 00:33:43,169
I'm only joking.

519
00:33:43,169 --> 00:33:45,890
I'm sure he's a very interesting person...

520
00:33:45,890 --> 00:33:49,679
as well as good to look at!'

521
00:33:49,679 --> 00:33:54,990
At the Fisherman's Arms, they had crab salads
and ice-cold beer.

522
00:33:54,990 --> 00:33:59,860
They sat outside in friendly silence and watched
the activity on the beach.

523
00:33:59,860 --> 00:34:04,730
'Shall we walk over in that direction this
afternoon?'

524
00:34:04,730 --> 00:34:06,230
Stephen pointed to the left.

525
00:34:06,230 --> 00:34:11,419
'We could go along the coast path - see what
there is over the hill.'

526
00:34:11,419 --> 00:34:16,909
'OK, but let's not hurry off just yet,' said
Anna.

527
00:34:16,909 --> 00:34:19,060
They got some more drinks.

528
00:34:19,060 --> 00:34:24,429
Anna stretched out her long legs in the sun
and started to read the guidebook for the

529
00:34:24,429 --> 00:34:26,240
area.

530
00:34:26,240 --> 00:34:29,899
Stephen watched her while drinking his beer.

531
00:34:29,899 --> 00:34:31,899
Everything about her seemed so familiar.

532
00:34:31,899 --> 00:34:38,079
'She looks so happy sitting there, like a
cat in the sun,' he thought.

533
00:34:38,079 --> 00:34:44,550
'She's got a lovely face, so full of life
and smiles - except when I worry her with

534
00:34:44,550 --> 00:34:47,200
my silences.'

535
00:34:47,200 --> 00:34:50,310
He suddenly heard a loud voice behind him.

536
00:34:50,310 --> 00:34:54,270
'Bloody Tristan,' said a man at another table.

537
00:34:54,270 --> 00:34:56,760
'He thinks he owns the village.

538
00:34:56,760 --> 00:34:59,260
Why does he want to buy another house?

539
00:34:59,260 --> 00:35:00,410
He's already got two.

540
00:35:00,410 --> 00:35:03,600
How many more does he want?'

541
00:35:03,600 --> 00:35:04,600
'Ssh.

542
00:35:04,600 --> 00:35:06,270
Not so loud, Jack.

543
00:35:06,270 --> 00:35:12,160
In any case, you don't know if he does yet,'
said the man sitting with him in a low voice.

544
00:35:12,160 --> 00:35:16,600
'Well, you heard him asking about how much
the cottage was being sold for.

545
00:35:16,600 --> 00:35:19,510
He wants it, I'm sure,' said Jack.

546
00:35:19,510 --> 00:35:25,130
'Then he'll rent it out as a holiday place,
just like he's done with Dolphin Cottage.'

547
00:35:25,130 --> 00:35:29,870
Anna and Stephen sat there, pretending not
to listen.

548
00:35:29,870 --> 00:35:35,220
'Come on, he's got to rent Dolphin Cottage
out, he can't live in two places at once,

549
00:35:35,220 --> 00:35:36,580
can he?

550
00:35:36,580 --> 00:35:40,310
In any case, that woman, what's her name,
Jane...

551
00:35:40,310 --> 00:35:43,700
Jill, has been living there,' the other man
said.

552
00:35:43,700 --> 00:35:46,560
'Well, she doesn't live there now, does she?'

553
00:35:46,560 --> 00:35:47,599
replied Jack.

554
00:35:47,599 --> 00:35:53,300
'I don't know, he talks a lot about trying
to keep the village the same - "unspoilt",

555
00:35:53,300 --> 00:35:57,930
that's what he says - but if you ask me, it'll
be ruined in a few years' time.'

556
00:35:57,930 --> 00:36:04,410
'This place has stood here for a few hundred
years, I'm sure it'll go on a bit longer.

557
00:36:04,410 --> 00:36:09,540
Anyway, I don't believe Tristan'll buy another
cottage - why should he?'

558
00:36:09,540 --> 00:36:14,810
'I asked him this morning, and he didn't say
no,' Jack answered.

559
00:36:14,810 --> 00:36:19,710
'Knowing you, you probably didn't give him
time to answer your question before you got

560
00:36:19,710 --> 00:36:23,030
angry with him,' the other man replied.

561
00:36:23,030 --> 00:36:30,280
The man called Jack left the pub, still complaining
about 'bloody Tristan'.

562
00:36:30,280 --> 00:36:33,790
The other man stayed at the bar, staring into
his beer.

563
00:36:33,790 --> 00:36:34,790
'Help!'

564
00:36:34,790 --> 00:36:36,109
whispered Anna.

565
00:36:36,109 --> 00:36:42,070
'I'm glad he didn't realise we were the people
renting Dolphin Cottage.'

566
00:36:42,070 --> 00:36:44,550
'Come on,' said Stephen, standing up.

567
00:36:44,550 --> 00:36:47,849
'Let's go for our walk.'

568
00:36:47,849 --> 00:36:52,000
They walked out of the village along the coast
path.

569
00:36:52,000 --> 00:36:56,900
Although they talked about what they'd heard
in the bar, they were not really worried - just

570
00:36:56,900 --> 00:37:02,060
interested in the life of the village and
what part Tristan Goddard played in it.

571
00:37:02,060 --> 00:37:07,530
They knew that over the next three weeks they'd
probably discover what it was all about.

572
00:37:07,530 --> 00:37:15,250
They followed the path through some trees,
happy to escape from the hot sun for a while.

573
00:37:15,250 --> 00:37:20,650
Eventually, they walked round a corner and
came to a wide bay with people surfing on

574
00:37:20,650 --> 00:37:22,980
beautiful, white waves.

575
00:37:22,980 --> 00:37:26,050
'Hey, that looks fun,' said Stephen.

576
00:37:26,050 --> 00:37:28,540
'I've always wanted to try it.'

577
00:37:28,540 --> 00:37:32,490
'I did it once when I was about fifteen,'
said Anna.

578
00:37:32,490 --> 00:37:35,060
'I wasn't very good at it.

579
00:37:35,060 --> 00:37:37,730
Every time I stood up, I fell off.

580
00:37:37,730 --> 00:37:39,160
But I'll have another go.

581
00:37:39,160 --> 00:37:41,710
Age might have improved my balance.'

582
00:37:41,710 --> 00:37:49,109
A woman in the beach shop told them they could
hire surfboards there and, if they wanted,

583
00:37:49,109 --> 00:37:51,150
they could also have lessons.

584
00:37:51,150 --> 00:37:52,250
'Right.

585
00:37:52,250 --> 00:37:55,660
So, there's no reason why we shouldn't try,
then.

586
00:37:55,660 --> 00:37:57,290
Thanks for the information.

587
00:37:57,290 --> 00:38:02,150
We'll be back another day,' Stephen smiled.

588
00:38:02,150 --> 00:38:06,890
They walked slowly back towards Polreath,
changed into their swimming things at the

589
00:38:06,890 --> 00:38:10,359
cottage and went down to the beach.

590
00:38:10,359 --> 00:38:16,420
The sand was warm from the day's sun and Stephen
fell asleep lying there.

591
00:38:16,420 --> 00:38:19,700
Anna continued reading her local guidebook.

592
00:38:19,700 --> 00:38:24,500
This was always the first thing she bought
when she went to a new place, and a map of

593
00:38:24,500 --> 00:38:26,760
the area.

594
00:38:26,760 --> 00:38:31,981
She enjoyed getting information, which she'd
then pass on to Stephen - who, actually, didn't

595
00:38:31,981 --> 00:38:33,760
always want to know!

596
00:38:33,760 --> 00:38:38,619
In fact, she sometimes annoyed him with her
facts.

597
00:38:38,619 --> 00:38:44,650
Stephen woke up, saw Anna with her nose in
the book and knew that tonight in the restaurant

598
00:38:44,650 --> 00:38:49,400
she was going to say, 'I read in the guide
book that...'

599
00:38:49,400 --> 00:38:51,369
many times!

600
00:38:51,369 --> 00:38:55,830
He turned over quietly and ran his finger
down her back.

601
00:38:55,830 --> 00:38:58,010
'Oh, hello!

602
00:38:58,010 --> 00:38:59,579
Had a good sleep?

603
00:38:59,579 --> 00:39:03,790
You probably needed it after your early start
this morning.'

604
00:39:03,790 --> 00:39:05,170
'Mmm.'

605
00:39:05,170 --> 00:39:06,750
He stood up and stretched.

606
00:39:06,750 --> 00:39:09,319
'Time for a swim?'

607
00:39:09,319 --> 00:39:11,890
'Why not,' she replied.

608
00:39:11,890 --> 00:39:21,900
'Then I'm going home for a quick sleep before
dinner.'

609
00:39:21,900 --> 00:39:23,670
CHAPTER FIVE

610
00:39:23,670 --> 00:39:26,890
Philpots

611
00:39:26,890 --> 00:39:31,680
Sitting at dinner in Philpots that evening,
Anna felt wonderful.

612
00:39:31,680 --> 00:39:39,000
The fresh air, the sun, the swimming, everything
had made her feel so alive.

613
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:44,470
She found it hard to remember the Anna of
a few days ago, and she almost couldn't recognise

614
00:39:44,470 --> 00:39:47,920
Stephen he looked so relaxed.

615
00:39:47,920 --> 00:39:50,130
'You've got a red nose,' she said.

616
00:39:50,130 --> 00:39:53,930
'It's not red, it's the light in this restaurant.

617
00:39:53,930 --> 00:39:56,240
And have you seen yours, by the way?'

618
00:39:56,240 --> 00:40:00,800
'Yes, it looks very healthy,' she replied.

619
00:40:00,800 --> 00:40:04,790
'Why is mine red and yours healthy?' he laughed.

620
00:40:04,790 --> 00:40:06,990
'What are you having?'

621
00:40:06,990 --> 00:40:08,880
she asked, changing the subject.

622
00:40:08,880 --> 00:40:11,079
'Need you ask?' said Stephen.

623
00:40:11,079 --> 00:40:12,280
'Lobster, of course.

624
00:40:12,280 --> 00:40:13,280
And you?'

625
00:40:13,280 --> 00:40:14,280
'The same.

626
00:40:14,280 --> 00:40:17,930
Do you think it's one of Tristan's?'

627
00:40:17,930 --> 00:40:22,520
'Will we be able to taste the difference?'
he joked.

628
00:40:22,520 --> 00:40:27,890
Anna knew that over dinner, Stephen would
probably find it easy to start talking about

629
00:40:27,890 --> 00:40:32,800
the things that were making him unhappy, but
she didn't want him to.

630
00:40:32,800 --> 00:40:39,310
She wanted a relaxed, uncomplicated meal - an
evening without thinking about London, work

631
00:40:39,310 --> 00:40:41,510
or Stephen's problems.

632
00:40:41,510 --> 00:40:45,440
So she deliberately kept the conversation
away from anything serious.

633
00:40:45,440 --> 00:40:48,020
'Hey, look at that!

634
00:40:48,020 --> 00:40:54,900
Doesn't it look wonderful,' Anna said when
the waiter brought their plates to the table.

635
00:40:54,900 --> 00:41:00,290
The warm lobster pieces covered each plate,
and a little bowl of extra sauce came with

636
00:41:00,290 --> 00:41:01,640
it.

637
00:41:01,640 --> 00:41:08,490
She dipped some bread into the sauce, 'This
is seriously delicious!'

638
00:41:08,490 --> 00:41:14,850
The lobster was followed by a lime and lemon
dessert, and a wonderful selection of cheeses.

639
00:41:14,850 --> 00:41:17,240
They finished with strong coffee.

640
00:41:17,240 --> 00:41:23,190
'We're going to be all right here, aren't
we?' said Anna as they stood up to go.

641
00:41:23,190 --> 00:41:27,210
'I think this is going to turn out to be our
best holiday ever.'

642
00:41:27,210 --> 00:41:30,810
'I hope so,' said Stephen.

643
00:41:30,810 --> 00:41:33,640
Just as they were leaving, Tristan arrived.

644
00:41:33,640 --> 00:41:34,770
'Evening.

645
00:41:34,770 --> 00:41:37,220
I thought you might be here,' he said.

646
00:41:37,220 --> 00:41:41,640
'I just wondered if you'd like to come fishing
tomorrow morning Stephen?

647
00:41:41,640 --> 00:41:46,910
You obviously get up early and I usually go
out about six, six thirty for a couple of

648
00:41:46,910 --> 00:41:47,910
hours.

649
00:41:47,910 --> 00:41:50,020
You too, Anna, if you'd like.'

650
00:41:50,020 --> 00:41:53,619
'Thanks, Tristan,' said Stephen, 'I'd enjoy
that.

651
00:41:53,619 --> 00:41:55,680
What about you, Anna?'

652
00:41:55,680 --> 00:41:59,339
'I'd rather have a bit longer in bed tomorrow
morning.

653
00:41:59,339 --> 00:42:01,369
I'm still catching up on my sleep.

654
00:42:01,369 --> 00:42:04,010
But you go, Stephen.'

655
00:42:04,010 --> 00:42:08,099
'Meet me at the harbour at about six tomorrow
then,' said Tristan.

656
00:42:08,099 --> 00:42:11,030
'It's a blue boat called Wave Dancer.'

657
00:42:11,030 --> 00:42:12,330
'Right.

658
00:42:12,330 --> 00:42:15,849
See you there, and thanks again.

659
00:42:15,849 --> 00:42:16,849
Goodnight.'

660
00:42:16,849 --> 00:42:20,790
'That should be interesting,' said Anna to
Stephen as they walked home.

661
00:42:20,790 --> 00:42:26,119
'I shall expect you to find out everything
about him - all that business with that man

662
00:42:26,119 --> 00:42:32,080
in the pub yesterday, who the woman is who
lived in our cottage - everything, please.'

663
00:42:32,080 --> 00:42:37,770
'I'm going fishing, I'm not going to question
him about his private life!'

664
00:42:37,770 --> 00:42:38,770
Stephen laughed.

665
00:42:38,770 --> 00:42:43,910
'If I catch anything we can have it for tomorrow
night's dinner, can't we?'

666
00:42:43,910 --> 00:42:47,760
'Yes, but don't bring home a lobster, please.

667
00:42:47,760 --> 00:42:49,980
I don't know whether I could cook one of those.

668
00:42:49,980 --> 00:42:55,220
They're alive when you put them in boiling
water and they make a terrible noise.

669
00:42:55,220 --> 00:43:00,390
I know it's stupid but I'd rather eat lobster
at Philpots and not hear them dying.'

670
00:43:00,390 --> 00:43:03,160
'Don't worry,' Stephen said.

671
00:43:03,160 --> 00:43:06,200
'I don't expect Tristan will let me have one.

672
00:43:06,200 --> 00:43:11,680
I should think he needs to sell the expensive
stuff to make some money'

673
00:43:11,680 --> 00:43:17,609
At six the next morning, Tristan was waiting
on his boat, Wave Dancer.

674
00:43:17,609 --> 00:43:22,260
He was dressed in the shorts he seemed to
live in during the hot weather.

675
00:43:22,260 --> 00:43:26,290
He was wondering why he'd asked Stephen and
Anna to come with him.

676
00:43:26,290 --> 00:43:30,890
He didn't usually ask the Dolphin Cottage
people out on his boat in his 'private' time,

677
00:43:30,890 --> 00:43:36,349
but there was something he liked about Stephen
and Anna - they were different.

678
00:43:36,349 --> 00:43:41,819
But was he feeling just the smallest bit of
disappointment that it was only Stephen who

679
00:43:41,819 --> 00:43:44,110
was coming?

680
00:43:44,110 --> 00:43:49,599
He turned and looked up at Dolphin Cottage,
just in time to see Stephen coming out, pulling

681
00:43:49,599 --> 00:43:52,349
a black T-shirt over his head.

682
00:43:52,349 --> 00:43:55,650
A few minutes later, he jumped onto the boat.

683
00:43:55,650 --> 00:43:58,060
'Am I late?

684
00:43:58,060 --> 00:43:59,650
Sorry,' he said.

685
00:43:59,650 --> 00:44:03,380
'Had a bit of difficulty waking up this morning.

686
00:44:03,380 --> 00:44:06,770
Could be something to do with the excellent
wine last night!'

687
00:44:06,770 --> 00:44:08,420
Tristan smiled.

688
00:44:08,420 --> 00:44:12,980
'Do you know anything about boats?' he asked.

689
00:44:12,980 --> 00:44:14,070
'Sure.

690
00:44:14,070 --> 00:44:15,580
I'm used to boats.

691
00:44:15,580 --> 00:44:23,060
We always had holidays by the sea when I was
a kid, and my parents taught me what to do.'

692
00:44:23,060 --> 00:44:27,910
They left the harbour and turned north following
the coast.

693
00:44:27,910 --> 00:44:32,000
Tristan dropped some lobster pots into the
sea and said he'd collect them later that

694
00:44:32,000 --> 00:44:33,770
day.

695
00:44:33,770 --> 00:44:37,560
The sea was calm as they continued northwards.

696
00:44:37,560 --> 00:44:42,750
It was a bit cooler on the water than on the
land and Stephen was pleased he'd remembered

697
00:44:42,750 --> 00:44:44,960
his sweater.

698
00:44:44,960 --> 00:44:49,040
He'd left Anna in bed, sleeping like a baby.

699
00:44:49,040 --> 00:44:53,060
She hadn't even woken up when he'd dropped
his keys on the floor.

700
00:44:53,060 --> 00:44:54,660
Lucky her!

701
00:44:54,660 --> 00:44:59,510
Being out on the sea was beginning to work
its magic.

702
00:44:59,510 --> 00:45:05,200
As the boat rose and fell gently, Stephen
remembered his excitement as a child on fishing

703
00:45:05,200 --> 00:45:07,089
trips with his father.

704
00:45:07,089 --> 00:45:13,530
His memories of his childhood holidays were
of fishing with his father for hours, not

705
00:45:13,530 --> 00:45:17,450
saying much but enjoying the activity.

706
00:45:17,450 --> 00:45:21,800
It was one of the few times they'd spent a
lot of time together.

707
00:45:21,800 --> 00:45:23,490
Now it was too late.

708
00:45:23,490 --> 00:45:29,840
His father had died a year ago from an unexpected
heart attack, leaving Stephen full of things

709
00:45:29,840 --> 00:45:32,500
he'd wanted to say to him.

710
00:45:32,500 --> 00:45:35,930
Today, the sea was calm.

711
00:45:35,930 --> 00:45:40,050
The sun made the tops of the waves dance and
shine.

712
00:45:40,050 --> 00:45:46,320
And when Tristan stopped the boat there was
silence, no more noise from the engine, just

713
00:45:46,320 --> 00:45:50,640
the rather sad sounds from a few seagulls.

714
00:45:50,640 --> 00:45:54,390
Together they started fishing off the back
of the boat.

715
00:45:54,390 --> 00:45:59,300
After a few minutes Tristan said, 'Got one.'

716
00:45:59,300 --> 00:46:02,920
He pulled in the fish and said, 'Mm, a mackerel.

717
00:46:02,920 --> 00:46:07,390
Nothing special, but quite nice grilled on
the barbecue.

718
00:46:07,390 --> 00:46:10,210
Right, I can relax now.

719
00:46:10,210 --> 00:46:14,200
I always think it's a good sign to catch the
first fish quickly.

720
00:46:14,200 --> 00:46:17,130
I think we're going to have an excellent couple
of hours.'

721
00:46:17,130 --> 00:46:22,849
'I hope so,' replied Stephen, Anna wants something
for tonight's dinner.'

722
00:46:22,849 --> 00:46:26,559
'Are you both OK in Dolphin Cottage?

723
00:46:26,559 --> 00:46:28,570
It's not very modern, I'm afraid.

724
00:46:28,570 --> 00:46:30,530
I haven't done much to it, really.

725
00:46:30,530 --> 00:46:35,180
My grandmother lived there all her life and
she left it to me when she died four years

726
00:46:35,180 --> 00:46:36,180
ago.'

727
00:46:36,180 --> 00:46:38,380
'We're absolutely fine.

728
00:46:38,380 --> 00:46:39,569
We love it.

729
00:46:39,569 --> 00:46:43,599
Actually, I don't think we'll ever want to
leave it.'

730
00:46:43,599 --> 00:46:45,490
Tristan looked at him rather sharply.

731
00:46:45,490 --> 00:46:46,490
'Sorry.

732
00:46:46,490 --> 00:46:49,930
Have I said something wrong?' said Stephen.

733
00:46:49,930 --> 00:46:52,630
'No, not at all.'

734
00:46:52,630 --> 00:46:54,100
Tristan shook his head.

735
00:46:54,100 --> 00:46:58,200
'I was just remembering someone else who said
that about the cottage.

736
00:46:58,200 --> 00:47:02,829
But in fact she did leave in the end.'

737
00:47:02,829 --> 00:47:05,890
'You're very lucky to live in such a beautiful
place.

738
00:47:05,890 --> 00:47:08,109
Have you always lived here?'

739
00:47:08,109 --> 00:47:12,140
Stephen was interested in getting people to
talk about themselves - and it was easier

740
00:47:12,140 --> 00:47:14,460
than talking about himself.

741
00:47:14,460 --> 00:47:20,380
'Yes, except when I went away for four years
to university.'

742
00:47:20,380 --> 00:47:22,869
Stephen hadn't expected that.

743
00:47:22,869 --> 00:47:28,330
Apparently, Tristan had left Polreath when
he was eighteen and had been very excited

744
00:47:28,330 --> 00:47:29,589
about living in a city.

745
00:47:29,589 --> 00:47:34,200
But he'd found that he missed the sea and
the open spaces.

746
00:47:34,200 --> 00:47:39,650
'Now, when I have to go to London, I look
at people's faces and see how difficult life

747
00:47:39,650 --> 00:47:42,160
is for a lot of them,' Tristan explained.

748
00:47:42,160 --> 00:47:45,420
All that running about and all that fear.

749
00:47:45,420 --> 00:47:49,420
You know - fear of crime, fear of losing your
job.

750
00:47:49,420 --> 00:47:51,350
I couldn't live like that.

751
00:47:51,350 --> 00:47:52,770
I've tried and I know.

752
00:47:52,770 --> 00:47:55,089
Polreath is home for me.

753
00:47:55,089 --> 00:47:56,609
I know it is.'

754
00:47:56,609 --> 00:47:59,309
'Have you got any family here?'

755
00:47:59,309 --> 00:48:00,309
asked Stephen.

756
00:48:00,309 --> 00:48:03,809
'Only my sister now,' Tristan replied.

757
00:48:03,809 --> 00:48:07,290
My parents moved away when my father retired
from fishing.

758
00:48:07,290 --> 00:48:10,470
But my sister and I are very close.

759
00:48:10,470 --> 00:48:13,710
She's happy here, like me.'

760
00:48:13,710 --> 00:48:18,560
Stephen listened to what Tristan was saying
and, for the first time, he began to feel

761
00:48:18,560 --> 00:48:19,829
he understood.

762
00:48:19,829 --> 00:48:25,990
Of course, he'd heard other people say how
hard city living was, and he'd even said it

763
00:48:25,990 --> 00:48:27,670
himself.

764
00:48:27,670 --> 00:48:32,490
In fact, last year when they were on their
way home from two weeks' holiday in Greece,

765
00:48:32,490 --> 00:48:38,090
he'd suggested to Anna that they should sell
their house and move to somewhere peaceful.

766
00:48:38,090 --> 00:48:41,119
But he'd known it was only a dream.

767
00:48:41,119 --> 00:48:46,319
When he'd gone back to the agency the following
Monday he found he enjoyed the office politics

768
00:48:46,319 --> 00:48:53,240
and the competition for new business - it
made him feel alive and at the centre of things.

769
00:48:53,240 --> 00:48:56,530
But now, something was different.

770
00:48:56,530 --> 00:49:00,420
Perhaps it was because everything at work
was so uncertain.

771
00:49:00,420 --> 00:49:03,700
Again, there was silence in the boat.

772
00:49:03,700 --> 00:49:08,660
Both men watched the water to see if any fish
were biting, and both men were deep in their

773
00:49:08,660 --> 00:49:10,059
own thoughts.

774
00:49:10,059 --> 00:49:16,599
They each caught some fish - mainly mackerel
- and Tristan talked a little more about Polreath

775
00:49:16,599 --> 00:49:19,450
and his life there.

776
00:49:19,450 --> 00:49:24,660
Stephen liked the easy way in which Tristan
talked; he knew that that was how Anna would

777
00:49:24,660 --> 00:49:26,780
like him to be.

778
00:49:26,780 --> 00:49:30,869
'Well, we'd better go back, I suppose,' said
Tristan.

779
00:49:30,869 --> 00:49:32,710
'I've got a trip to do later.

780
00:49:32,710 --> 00:49:35,339
How many have you caught?'

781
00:49:35,339 --> 00:49:36,339
'Four.

782
00:49:36,339 --> 00:49:38,880
Not bad for a city boy!'

783
00:49:38,880 --> 00:49:40,020
Stephen replied.

784
00:49:40,020 --> 00:49:47,520
There was something in Stephen's voice that
made Tristan look at him.

785
00:49:47,520 --> 00:49:49,240
CHAPTER SIX

786
00:49:49,240 --> 00:49:50,240
The phone call

787
00:49:50,240 --> 00:49:57,240
Anna was in the front garden of Dolphin Cottage
and she waved as she saw the boat come in

788
00:49:57,240 --> 00:49:59,700
to the harbour.

789
00:49:59,700 --> 00:50:03,510
'You two seem very happy together,' said Tristan.

790
00:50:03,510 --> 00:50:05,520
'Yes,' Stephen agreed.

791
00:50:05,520 --> 00:50:11,260
They had known Tristan for only a few days
and it seemed to Stephen a rather personal

792
00:50:11,260 --> 00:50:12,660
thing to say.

793
00:50:12,660 --> 00:50:15,390
But then Stephen realised he didn't mind.

794
00:50:15,390 --> 00:50:19,980
'Have you got anyone special?' he asked.

795
00:50:19,980 --> 00:50:26,380
'Sort of,' Tristan replied, and busied himself
tying up the boat to the harbour side.

796
00:50:26,380 --> 00:50:31,339
He didn't really feel like going into detail
about it at that moment.

797
00:50:31,339 --> 00:50:34,950
One reason was that he was thinking about
Anna, not Jill.

798
00:50:34,950 --> 00:50:38,270
'Thanks for the trip,' said Stephen.

799
00:50:38,270 --> 00:50:39,690
'It was great.

800
00:50:39,690 --> 00:50:45,180
By the way, if you're not doing anything tonight,
would you like to come and have dinner with

801
00:50:45,180 --> 00:50:46,180
us?

802
00:50:46,180 --> 00:50:48,380
We could barbecue the fish.

803
00:50:48,380 --> 00:50:50,240
Bring your friend, if you want.'

804
00:50:50,240 --> 00:50:51,240
'OK.

805
00:50:51,240 --> 00:50:52,240
Thanks.

806
00:50:52,240 --> 00:50:58,369
It'll just be me though,' said Tristan, pleased
at the thought of seeing Anna again.

807
00:50:58,369 --> 00:50:59,660
'Fine.

808
00:50:59,660 --> 00:51:02,119
See you about eight, then.'

809
00:51:02,119 --> 00:51:06,329
Stephen walked up from the harbour, and held
up his fish to show Anna.

810
00:51:06,329 --> 00:51:10,430
But when he got nearer, he could see that
something was wrong.

811
00:51:10,430 --> 00:51:13,510
'What's the matter?' he asked.

812
00:51:13,510 --> 00:51:15,310
'Has something happened?'

813
00:51:15,310 --> 00:51:17,530
'Afraid so.

814
00:51:17,530 --> 00:51:21,770
Rebecca's just phoned and said your office
need you to ring them immediately.'

815
00:51:21,770 --> 00:51:22,900
'Oh shit!

816
00:51:22,900 --> 00:51:27,660
I knew we shouldn't have left our number with
Rebecca!' he said angrily.

817
00:51:27,660 --> 00:51:29,210
'What the hell do they want?

818
00:51:29,210 --> 00:51:34,780
I don't feel like ringing them back.

819
00:51:34,780 --> 00:51:37,970
I think I just won't, and pretend we never
got the message.

820
00:51:37,970 --> 00:51:42,369
Do you know if Rebecca told the office she
knew where we were?'

821
00:51:42,369 --> 00:51:47,910
'Apparently she said she'd pass the message
on to you, so I guess you'll have to contact

822
00:51:47,910 --> 00:51:48,910
them.'

823
00:51:48,910 --> 00:51:50,869
'Oh bloody hell.'

824
00:51:50,869 --> 00:51:55,020
Stephen threw the fish down on the table and
went inside.

825
00:51:55,020 --> 00:52:00,069
She could hear him in the kitchen, noisily
making a cup of coffee.

826
00:52:00,069 --> 00:52:03,490
She wondered what the problem was at his office.

827
00:52:03,490 --> 00:52:08,890
She had met Charlie Jardine, Stephen's boss,
a couple of times and he'd seemed to be a

828
00:52:08,890 --> 00:52:10,410
reasonable person.

829
00:52:10,410 --> 00:52:13,770
What was it all about?

830
00:52:13,770 --> 00:52:19,260
Stephen must be talking to him now - she could
hear his voice rising in anger, and then she

831
00:52:19,260 --> 00:52:21,740
heard him put the phone down with a bang.

832
00:52:21,740 --> 00:52:24,540
He came out and sat next to Anna.

833
00:52:24,540 --> 00:52:27,380
His face was red with anger.

834
00:52:27,380 --> 00:52:28,680
'Well?'

835
00:52:28,680 --> 00:52:29,859
she asked.

836
00:52:29,859 --> 00:52:34,540
'Charlie wants everybody back in the office
for a crisis meeting tomorrow.

837
00:52:34,540 --> 00:52:35,540
Everybody!

838
00:52:35,540 --> 00:52:38,619
And that includes me,' Stephen replied.

839
00:52:38,619 --> 00:52:40,720
'Another agency wants to buy our company'

840
00:52:40,720 --> 00:52:44,609
'Can't you talk about it on the phone?'

841
00:52:44,609 --> 00:52:46,010
Anna asked.

842
00:52:46,010 --> 00:52:52,140
'Apparently, things are happening so quickly
and he needs to be able to act fast.'

843
00:52:52,140 --> 00:52:56,330
Stephen stood up and started walking up and
down the tiny front garden.

844
00:52:56,330 --> 00:53:00,099
'And he says he wants to do what's best for
the company.

845
00:53:00,099 --> 00:53:02,210
He sounded really worried on the phone.'

846
00:53:02,210 --> 00:53:06,200
'So you're going then,' she said, rather coldly.

847
00:53:06,200 --> 00:53:07,990
''I'll have to.

848
00:53:07,990 --> 00:53:12,230
Mark's been called back from a conference
in Italy as well.'

849
00:53:12,230 --> 00:53:15,260
'That's work, not a holiday,' said Anna sharply.

850
00:53:15,260 --> 00:53:16,260
'I know.

851
00:53:16,260 --> 00:53:21,290
Look, I'm sorry.'

852
00:53:21,290 --> 00:53:22,960
Stephen put his arms round her.

853
00:53:22,960 --> 00:53:27,530
'I know this has ruined things for you as
well.

854
00:53:27,530 --> 00:53:31,930
If I go this morning, I'll come back straight
after the meeting.

855
00:53:31,930 --> 00:53:36,310
I'll drive through the night if I have to,
but I promise I'll be back for breakfast on

856
00:53:36,310 --> 00:53:38,630
Thursday'

857
00:53:38,630 --> 00:53:41,160
'Could you lose your job if someone buys the
company?'

858
00:53:41,160 --> 00:53:42,200
Anna asked.

859
00:53:42,200 --> 00:53:46,220
'Yes, it's quite possible,' Stephen said.

860
00:53:46,220 --> 00:53:49,220
'It's also possible I could lose it anyway.

861
00:53:49,220 --> 00:53:53,640
The agency is obviously in a bad way, as far
as money goes.'

862
00:53:53,640 --> 00:53:59,349
'Oh Stephen - just when we were beginning
to relax here.

863
00:53:59,349 --> 00:54:04,599
It's not fair!' said Anna, close to tears.

864
00:54:04,599 --> 00:54:08,730
Stephen finished his coffee and went back
into the cottage.

865
00:54:08,730 --> 00:54:10,849
Anna continued to sit in the front garden.

866
00:54:10,849 --> 00:54:17,920
Half an hour later, Stephen appeared, carrying
a small bag and wearing his work trousers.

867
00:54:17,920 --> 00:54:22,590
'I'll walk with you to the car,' said Anna.

868
00:54:22,590 --> 00:54:27,799
It felt unreal to both of them - him going,
her staying.

869
00:54:27,799 --> 00:54:31,750
She could see that Stephen's mind was already
full of work.

870
00:54:31,750 --> 00:54:37,579
The inside of the car was hot from being in
the sun, so they opened all the doors to let

871
00:54:37,579 --> 00:54:40,010
some air in.

872
00:54:40,010 --> 00:54:43,640
'You'll be OK on your own for two days, won't
you?' said Stephen.

873
00:54:43,640 --> 00:54:48,450
'Yes, no problem, Don't worry about me.

874
00:54:48,450 --> 00:54:50,910
You just be careful driving.

875
00:54:50,910 --> 00:54:52,770
Take care, please.'

876
00:54:52,770 --> 00:54:54,329
'I will.

877
00:54:54,329 --> 00:54:55,900
Bye love.'

878
00:54:55,900 --> 00:54:56,900
'Bye.

879
00:54:56,900 --> 00:55:01,840
I don't know what to say... good luck, I suppose.

880
00:55:01,840 --> 00:55:07,160
Ring me tonight from home - I want to know
you're there.'

881
00:55:07,160 --> 00:55:09,270
Anna watched Stephen drive away.

882
00:55:09,270 --> 00:55:21,640
'Poor man,' she thought, and then selfishly,
'I'm pleased I don't have to go, too.'

883
00:55:21,640 --> 00:55:24,069
CHAPTER SEVEN

884
00:55:24,069 --> 00:55:27,670
Tristan comes for dinner

885
00:55:27,670 --> 00:55:29,650
Anna had a pleasant day.

886
00:55:29,650 --> 00:55:31,270
It was difficult not to.

887
00:55:31,270 --> 00:55:38,270
Polreath was the same interesting place and
the weather was wonderful again.

888
00:55:38,270 --> 00:55:41,619
She walked around and did a bit of shopping.

889
00:55:41,619 --> 00:55:45,589
Some people in the village were beginning
to greet her, 'Morning.

890
00:55:45,589 --> 00:55:50,950
Another nice day,' they said, and she smiled
back.

891
00:55:50,950 --> 00:55:55,589
She sat in the front garden of the cottage,
reading and watching all the comings and goings

892
00:55:55,589 --> 00:55:57,450
in the harbour.

893
00:55:57,450 --> 00:56:02,059
She was learning to recognise some of the
different boats - which ones were fishing

894
00:56:02,059 --> 00:56:06,270
boats, and which ones were owned by visitors.

895
00:56:06,270 --> 00:56:11,740
Tristan's boat, full of passengers, went out,
and she decided she'd find out where he was

896
00:56:11,740 --> 00:56:13,270
going the next day.

897
00:56:13,270 --> 00:56:19,210
It might be nice to do something with other
people tomorrow, she thought.

898
00:56:19,210 --> 00:56:23,329
She looked at Stephen's fish in the fridge
and remembered how pleased he'd looked when

899
00:56:23,329 --> 00:56:26,300
he'd got off Tristan's boat earlier that day.

900
00:56:26,300 --> 00:56:29,500
'I'll have some later,' she thought.

901
00:56:29,500 --> 00:56:32,820
'Don't want to waste them.'

902
00:56:32,820 --> 00:56:36,839
In the late afternoon, she went for a swim.

903
00:56:36,839 --> 00:56:41,930
Back home, she showered and sat with a glass
of white wine in the front garden until the

904
00:56:41,930 --> 00:56:44,710
sun disappeared behind the hill.

905
00:56:44,710 --> 00:56:48,180
Then she went inside to get some dinner.

906
00:56:48,180 --> 00:56:52,150
There was a knock on the door, and Tristan
appeared.

907
00:56:52,150 --> 00:56:55,270
'Hello, I hope I'm not late.'

908
00:56:55,270 --> 00:56:57,650
'Pardon?' said Anna.

909
00:56:57,650 --> 00:57:00,450
'Late for what?'

910
00:57:00,450 --> 00:57:01,450
'Dinner.

911
00:57:01,450 --> 00:57:03,940
Stephen asked me for dinner.'

912
00:57:03,940 --> 00:57:06,099
Tristan could see something was wrong.

913
00:57:06,099 --> 00:57:08,130
'Oh, no!

914
00:57:08,130 --> 00:57:11,060
I can see you didn't know!'

915
00:57:11,060 --> 00:57:12,060
'I'm sorry.

916
00:57:12,060 --> 00:57:13,819
Come in.

917
00:57:13,819 --> 00:57:16,060
No, I didn't know.

918
00:57:16,060 --> 00:57:20,619
The thing is,' explained Anna, 'Stephen's
had to go back to London.

919
00:57:20,619 --> 00:57:26,160
He had a phone call when you were out fishing
this morning, and he's gone.'

920
00:57:26,160 --> 00:57:29,079
'Oh, I'm sorry.

921
00:57:29,079 --> 00:57:30,329
Is everything all right...?

922
00:57:30,329 --> 00:57:34,660
I mean, I hope nothing bad has happened.'

923
00:57:34,660 --> 00:57:40,060
Tristan meant what he said, but if he was
honest with himself, he was also pleased that

924
00:57:40,060 --> 00:57:44,579
Anna was now here alone, without Stephen.

925
00:57:44,579 --> 00:57:47,069
'It's a crisis at work,' Anna said.

926
00:57:47,069 --> 00:57:50,090
'He didn't want to leave but...

927
00:57:50,090 --> 00:57:53,039
He'll be back on Thursday, he says.'

928
00:57:53,039 --> 00:57:54,420
'Oh good.

929
00:57:54,420 --> 00:57:56,030
Anyway, I'll go.

930
00:57:56,030 --> 00:57:58,400
Don't worry about dinner,' said Tristan.

931
00:57:58,400 --> 00:58:00,910
'No, stay, really,' she said.

932
00:58:00,910 --> 00:58:03,130
'I was just grilling the fish.

933
00:58:03,130 --> 00:58:05,510
I can easily do some more.

934
00:58:05,510 --> 00:58:07,309
Help yourself to a glass of wine.'

935
00:58:07,309 --> 00:58:10,809
'Well, if you're sure.

936
00:58:10,809 --> 00:58:11,809
Thanks.'

937
00:58:11,809 --> 00:58:15,960
Tristan poured himself a drink and filled
up Anna's glass as well.

938
00:58:15,960 --> 00:58:19,500
'Can I do anything?' he asked.

939
00:58:19,500 --> 00:58:21,660
'You could cut the bread, if you want.

940
00:58:21,660 --> 00:58:24,270
And take all the plates and stuff outside.

941
00:58:24,270 --> 00:58:29,309
Is it OK with you if we eat outside?'

942
00:58:29,309 --> 00:58:30,309
'Fine.'

943
00:58:30,309 --> 00:58:33,190
Tristan carried everything into the front
garden and waited for Anna.

944
00:58:33,190 --> 00:58:40,520
He felt a bit strange sitting there, remembering
other times he'd had dinner at the cottage.

945
00:58:40,520 --> 00:58:45,230
Jill and he used to eat there most evenings
during their first summer together.

946
00:58:45,230 --> 00:58:50,650
But when she was here earlier this year, though,
she seemed to prefer to eat at his house or

947
00:58:50,650 --> 00:58:53,220
in the village somewhere.

948
00:58:53,220 --> 00:58:57,490
The cottage had become Jill's private world.

949
00:58:57,490 --> 00:58:59,039
Anna brought the fish.

950
00:58:59,039 --> 00:59:02,009
Strange, he thought, to himself.

951
00:59:02,009 --> 00:59:08,030
There's Jill and Stephen in London and Anna
and me here.

952
00:59:08,030 --> 00:59:10,930
Tristan talked a bit about his day.

953
00:59:10,930 --> 00:59:16,319
After the fishing that morning, he'd been
quite busy - two trips with a full boat each

954
00:59:16,319 --> 00:59:20,920
time, up the coast looking at the land from
the sea.

955
00:59:20,920 --> 00:59:25,720
He seemed surprised when she asked him if
he ever got bored doing the same trips every

956
00:59:25,720 --> 00:59:26,720
week.

957
00:59:26,720 --> 00:59:29,079
'Never bored,' he said.

958
00:59:29,079 --> 00:59:33,460
'Annoyed maybe at some of the stupid questions
people ask sometimes.

959
00:59:33,460 --> 00:59:38,589
But basically I can't think of a better way
of earning a living.'

960
00:59:38,589 --> 00:59:41,010
The phone rang and made them both jump.

961
00:59:41,010 --> 00:59:47,260
'That'll be Stephen, I hope,' said Anna and
went to answer it.

962
00:59:47,260 --> 00:59:52,030
Tristan sat and thought how much he liked
Anna's company.

963
00:59:52,030 --> 00:59:54,369
She came back out a few minutes later.

964
00:59:54,369 --> 00:59:56,319
'Yes, it was.

965
00:59:56,319 --> 01:00:00,990
He said sorry about tonight - about forgetting
to tell me you were coming to dinner.

966
01:00:00,990 --> 01:00:04,549
And he says London is hot, airless and dirty!'

967
01:00:04,549 --> 01:00:10,849
'Does he enjoy his job, whatever it is?' asked
Tristan.

968
01:00:10,849 --> 01:00:13,630
'He works for an advertising agency.

969
01:00:13,630 --> 01:00:17,010
To be honest, I don't know if he does enjoy
it any more.

970
01:00:17,010 --> 01:00:21,369
He used to, but recently something's changed.

971
01:00:21,369 --> 01:00:22,700
Maybe he's changed.

972
01:00:22,700 --> 01:00:28,630
He was hoping - well, actually, I was hoping
- this holiday would give him a chance to

973
01:00:28,630 --> 01:00:31,369
have a good think about it all.

974
01:00:31,369 --> 01:00:34,849
Perhaps now, the decisions will be taken for
him.

975
01:00:34,849 --> 01:00:38,730
He may come back on Thursday without a job.

976
01:00:38,730 --> 01:00:43,100
But, I'm sorry, you probably don't want to
hear all that.

977
01:00:43,100 --> 01:00:44,640
You were just being polite.'

978
01:00:44,640 --> 01:00:48,079
'No, I wasn't... if you understand me.

979
01:00:48,079 --> 01:00:49,579
I'm interested.

980
01:00:49,579 --> 01:00:51,819
I like the little I know about Stephen.

981
01:00:51,819 --> 01:00:55,950
I enjoyed our fishing trip this morning.'

982
01:00:55,950 --> 01:01:00,599
Tristan paused and then said, 'Maybe it's
my turn to be honest.

983
01:01:00,599 --> 01:01:06,080
You see, you and Stephen make me think about
myself and my...

984
01:01:06,080 --> 01:01:12,990
I don't know what to call her - woman-friend,
girl-friend, whatever.'

985
01:01:12,990 --> 01:01:15,869
Anna waited for him to go on.

986
01:01:15,869 --> 01:01:21,770
He told her about Jill and him and the difficulties
of continuing a long-distance relationship.

987
01:01:21,770 --> 01:01:26,079
He spoke quite openly about it all.

988
01:01:26,079 --> 01:01:29,360
Anna couldn't help comparing him with Stephen.

989
01:01:29,360 --> 01:01:33,740
Stephen always had such difficulty trying
to explain something personal.

990
01:01:33,740 --> 01:01:38,400
The death of his father had hit him hard but
he still hadn't really talked about it with

991
01:01:38,400 --> 01:01:39,890
her.

992
01:01:39,890 --> 01:01:45,720
Only once, about three months ago, when she'd
found him in the kitchen crying, then he'd

993
01:01:45,720 --> 01:01:48,520
managed to talk about it a bit.

994
01:01:48,520 --> 01:01:54,410
Poor darling Stephen, people who only saw
his public face just didn't know him.

995
01:01:54,410 --> 01:02:02,369
They opened another bottle of wine and carried
on talking - about him, about her and Stephen,

996
01:02:02,369 --> 01:02:05,830
about the village and the people who lived
there.

997
01:02:05,830 --> 01:02:09,349
Finally, Tristan stood up.

998
01:02:09,349 --> 01:02:11,289
'It's time I went.

999
01:02:11,289 --> 01:02:14,530
Thank you for a really nice evening.

1000
01:02:14,530 --> 01:02:16,690
You're a good listener.'

1001
01:02:16,690 --> 01:02:18,310
'So are you.'

1002
01:02:18,310 --> 01:02:21,119
'Shall I see you tomorrow?' he asked.

1003
01:02:21,119 --> 01:02:24,990
'Yes, I was thinking of coming on one of your
trips.

1004
01:02:24,990 --> 01:02:28,849
Where are you going in the morning?' asked
Anna.

1005
01:02:28,849 --> 01:02:31,890
'Out past Skellig and round the rocks.'

1006
01:02:31,890 --> 01:02:34,410
He took a step nearer her.

1007
01:02:34,410 --> 01:02:36,099
'It's a good trip.

1008
01:02:36,099 --> 01:02:37,200
The boat leaves at ten.'

1009
01:02:37,200 --> 01:02:38,609
'Fine.

1010
01:02:38,609 --> 01:02:42,620
I'll be there.'

1011
01:02:42,620 --> 01:02:46,540
Maybe it was the wine, but he seemed to be
standing closer.

1012
01:02:46,540 --> 01:02:52,900
He put his hands on her shoulders and kissed
her quite firmly on the lips.

1013
01:02:52,900 --> 01:02:54,170
'Goodnight.

1014
01:02:54,170 --> 01:03:02,170
See you in the morning,' he said, and closed
the gate behind him.

1015
01:03:02,170 --> 01:03:03,839
CHAPTER EIGHT

1016
01:03:03,839 --> 01:03:07,960
On Wave Dancer

1017
01:03:07,960 --> 01:03:13,650
When Anna woke the next morning, she forgot
that Stephen wasn't in bed next to her until

1018
01:03:13,650 --> 01:03:16,660
she turned over to touch him.

1019
01:03:16,660 --> 01:03:19,030
She looked at her watch - eight o'clock.

1020
01:03:19,030 --> 01:03:24,520
He'd be on his way to the office now, probably
caught in traffic.

1021
01:03:24,520 --> 01:03:27,119
Poor thing.

1022
01:03:27,119 --> 01:03:31,900
She lay there for a while thinking about him
and wondering how much today would change

1023
01:03:31,900 --> 01:03:33,730
their lives.

1024
01:03:33,730 --> 01:03:35,849
'Coffee,' she thought.

1025
01:03:35,849 --> 01:03:39,589
'And I think I'll go and get the newspaper.

1026
01:03:39,589 --> 01:03:43,970
I can do the crossword before I go on the
trip.'

1027
01:03:43,970 --> 01:03:49,880
On her way down to the shop, she started thinking
about last night's dinner with Tristan.

1028
01:03:49,880 --> 01:03:55,339
She wondered if today they'd be as easy with
each other as they'd been last night.

1029
01:03:55,339 --> 01:03:57,049
The woman in the shop said, 'Morning.

1030
01:03:57,049 --> 01:04:00,779
Did you have a nice dinner last night?'

1031
01:04:00,779 --> 01:04:05,970
'Yes, thank you,' said Anna in a surprised
voice.

1032
01:04:05,970 --> 01:04:10,720
The woman continued, 'I saw you when I was
walking my dog.

1033
01:04:10,720 --> 01:04:13,660
You can't keep anything secret in this place
for long!'

1034
01:04:13,660 --> 01:04:15,340
Anna laughed.

1035
01:04:15,340 --> 01:04:19,920
'I must remember that,' she thought.

1036
01:04:19,920 --> 01:04:26,670
Back home, she tried the crossword but it
was too difficult, so she left it for later.

1037
01:04:26,670 --> 01:04:30,480
She could see Tristan's boat below with Tristan
on board.

1038
01:04:30,480 --> 01:04:33,720
She noticed there was more movement on the
sea today.

1039
01:04:33,720 --> 01:04:38,839
It wasn't rough but the boats were moving
up and down a little.

1040
01:04:38,839 --> 01:04:44,410
She went inside to collect her backpack from
the cottage and went down to the harbour.

1041
01:04:44,410 --> 01:04:47,540
Tristan was by the boat, talking to another
man.

1042
01:04:47,540 --> 01:04:50,750
'Morning, Anna,' said Tristan.

1043
01:04:50,750 --> 01:04:52,349
'Everything OK?

1044
01:04:52,349 --> 01:04:55,619
This is Gary - he works with me on the boat
trips.

1045
01:04:55,619 --> 01:04:59,720
Anna's staying at Dolphin Cottage,' he said
to Gary.

1046
01:04:59,720 --> 01:05:01,569
They smiled at each other.

1047
01:05:01,569 --> 01:05:06,920
Gary looked at her quite closely and she wondered
if they'd been talking about her when she

1048
01:05:06,920 --> 01:05:07,920
arrived.

1049
01:05:07,920 --> 01:05:12,210
'I haven't got a ticket or anything for this
trip,' said Anna.

1050
01:05:12,210 --> 01:05:14,640
'Do I need one?'

1051
01:05:14,640 --> 01:05:15,980
'No,' replied Gary.

1052
01:05:15,980 --> 01:05:17,430
'You pay on the boat.

1053
01:05:17,430 --> 01:05:20,380
Have you got a jacket or something with you?

1054
01:05:20,380 --> 01:05:22,119
You might need it today.

1055
01:05:22,119 --> 01:05:26,910
We were just saying that the sea'll probably
be a bit rough on the other side of the island.'

1056
01:05:26,910 --> 01:05:30,920
'The water comes over the boat in certain
places.

1057
01:05:30,920 --> 01:05:35,549
Sit near the front on the right side if you
don't want to get wet,' Tristan added.

1058
01:05:35,549 --> 01:05:36,750
'Right.

1059
01:05:36,750 --> 01:05:37,940
Thanks.'

1060
01:05:37,940 --> 01:05:43,280
He jumped onto the boat and then turned to
help Anna.

1061
01:05:43,280 --> 01:05:45,910
He held out his hand and took hers very firmly.

1062
01:05:45,910 --> 01:05:50,430
He kept hold until she had sat down.

1063
01:05:50,430 --> 01:05:54,000
Other people were now arriving and getting
on the boat.

1064
01:05:54,000 --> 01:05:56,760
Most of them seemed to know Tristan.

1065
01:05:56,760 --> 01:05:58,910
Perhaps they went on his trips often.

1066
01:05:58,910 --> 01:06:05,920
Anna recognised one or two who she'd seen
on the beach or in the village somewhere.

1067
01:06:05,920 --> 01:06:13,010
Everybody seemed very well-prepared - jackets,
extra sweaters, binoculars, cameras.

1068
01:06:13,010 --> 01:06:16,619
Ready for a trans-Atlantic expedition, she
thought.

1069
01:06:16,619 --> 01:06:21,380
Then she looked at Tristan and Gary in their
shorts and T-shirts and wondered which group

1070
01:06:21,380 --> 01:06:24,350
had got it right.

1071
01:06:24,350 --> 01:06:28,720
Tristan started explaining to everyone where
they were going and what they might see on

1072
01:06:28,720 --> 01:06:29,720
the trip.

1073
01:06:29,720 --> 01:06:33,360
This gave her a good chance to look at him
carefully.

1074
01:06:33,360 --> 01:06:40,020
He told a few funny stories and the passengers
laughed in the right places.

1075
01:06:40,020 --> 01:06:45,510
Anna found herself thinking how attractive
he was - and not just physically.

1076
01:06:45,510 --> 01:06:49,550
He had an air of confidence about him that
she liked.

1077
01:06:49,550 --> 01:06:54,420
But then, he must have felt Anna's eyes on
him because he turned towards her and she

1078
01:06:54,420 --> 01:06:55,829
blushed!

1079
01:06:55,829 --> 01:06:58,400
She could feel her cheeks going red!

1080
01:06:58,400 --> 01:07:01,470
Just like a schoolgirl caught doing something
wrong!

1081
01:07:01,470 --> 01:07:03,849
How embarrassing!

1082
01:07:03,849 --> 01:07:09,100
As soon as they left the harbour, the sea
became much rougher but nobody seemed to be

1083
01:07:09,100 --> 01:07:10,270
worried.

1084
01:07:10,270 --> 01:07:15,080
In fact, it was quite fun trying to move your
body with the movement of the boat - a bit

1085
01:07:15,080 --> 01:07:18,490
like riding a horse, Anna thought.

1086
01:07:18,490 --> 01:07:24,540
Once or twice, when the boat went into a wave,
water came over the side, and again, people

1087
01:07:24,540 --> 01:07:27,839
seemed to think it was all part of the fun.

1088
01:07:27,839 --> 01:07:31,520
They passed the island and moved on towards
the rocks.

1089
01:07:31,520 --> 01:07:37,760
From Polreath, you couldn't really see very
much beyond the island so Anna was surprised

1090
01:07:37,760 --> 01:07:43,260
at the size of some of the rocks - almost
like mini-islands.

1091
01:07:43,260 --> 01:07:46,630
Tristan took the boat close in and slowed
the engine.

1092
01:07:46,630 --> 01:07:50,500
'There are very often seals around here.

1093
01:07:50,500 --> 01:07:56,380
In fact, we might see some young ones - the
first ones are usually born around this time,'

1094
01:07:56,380 --> 01:07:59,069
he said quietly.

1095
01:07:59,069 --> 01:08:01,690
'Look!' said a man at the back of the boat.

1096
01:08:01,690 --> 01:08:05,849
'There are two in the water over there.'

1097
01:08:05,849 --> 01:08:09,049
Everybody focused their binoculars where he
was pointing.

1098
01:08:09,049 --> 01:08:15,390
The heads of two adult seals appeared and
then disappeared behind a wave.

1099
01:08:15,390 --> 01:08:18,240
Someone tried to take a picture.

1100
01:08:18,240 --> 01:08:21,200
Tristan took the boat in and out of the rocks.

1101
01:08:21,200 --> 01:08:25,799
They managed to see some seals out of the
water - lying on rocks, almost sunbathing

1102
01:08:25,799 --> 01:08:29,060
- but no young ones.

1103
01:08:29,060 --> 01:08:34,009
They were about to turn for home when Gary
saw something white on the rocks just above

1104
01:08:34,009 --> 01:08:35,009
the water.

1105
01:08:35,009 --> 01:08:38,350
It was a very young seal.

1106
01:08:38,350 --> 01:08:41,859
'Don't make too much noise,' said Tristan.

1107
01:08:41,859 --> 01:08:46,710
'We don't want to frighten it, or worry its
Mum, wherever she is.

1108
01:08:46,710 --> 01:08:49,380
This is the first one I've seen this year.

1109
01:08:49,380 --> 01:08:53,100
I guess it's only a few days old.'

1110
01:08:53,100 --> 01:08:59,339
Not many people on the boat had ever seen
a young seal before so they were really pleased.

1111
01:08:59,339 --> 01:09:04,220
Anna thought how helpless it looked, all by
itself on the rock.

1112
01:09:04,220 --> 01:09:09,359
And as if he knew what she was thinking, Tristan
said, 'The first few days are dangerous ones

1113
01:09:09,359 --> 01:09:10,969
for the young.

1114
01:09:10,969 --> 01:09:16,219
Some of the bigger seabirds attack them - they
go for their eyes.'

1115
01:09:16,219 --> 01:09:21,330
The boat was moving up and down quite a lot
and it was difficult to stand.

1116
01:09:21,330 --> 01:09:28,170
Suddenly, the boat was caught by a bigger
wave and an elderly woman fell sideways.

1117
01:09:28,170 --> 01:09:32,410
In trying to save herself, she hit her arm
on the side.

1118
01:09:32,410 --> 01:09:36,100
Immediately, people crowded round her, and
started talking:

1119
01:09:36,100 --> 01:09:38,370
'Are you all right?'

1120
01:09:38,370 --> 01:09:40,609
'Here, let's get you up onto a seat.'

1121
01:09:40,609 --> 01:09:43,009
'Just sit quietly for a minute.

1122
01:09:43,009 --> 01:09:45,750
What a nasty shock!'

1123
01:09:45,750 --> 01:09:50,100
Tristan moved the boat out into deeper water,
away from the rocks.

1124
01:09:50,100 --> 01:09:55,100
He looked at Anna and his eyes seemed to be
asking her 'Could you?'

1125
01:09:55,100 --> 01:09:56,960
She went over to the woman.

1126
01:09:56,960 --> 01:09:59,010
'Would you like me to look?'

1127
01:09:59,010 --> 01:10:00,010
she said.

1128
01:10:00,010 --> 01:10:01,610
'I'm a nurse.'

1129
01:10:01,610 --> 01:10:04,270
'I'm all right,' she said.

1130
01:10:04,270 --> 01:10:09,370
'I think I just hurt my arm, that's all.'

1131
01:10:09,370 --> 01:10:13,510
Anna moved the woman and her husband up to
the front of the boat.

1132
01:10:13,510 --> 01:10:17,860
She looked at the arm, which was quite red
and already beginning to get bigger.

1133
01:10:17,860 --> 01:10:23,489
Very gently, she pressed and the woman made
a small sound.

1134
01:10:23,489 --> 01:10:27,960
'Well, Mrs... er...' Anna began.

1135
01:10:27,960 --> 01:10:29,100
'Taylor...

1136
01:10:29,100 --> 01:10:31,630
Sheila,' the woman said.

1137
01:10:31,630 --> 01:10:36,820
'Sheila, I don't think you've broken it, but
it'd be a good idea to have it X-rayed when

1138
01:10:36,820 --> 01:10:39,140
we get back, just to make sure.'

1139
01:10:39,140 --> 01:10:40,239
Anna looked up.

1140
01:10:40,239 --> 01:10:43,380
'Tristan, where's the nearest place for that?'

1141
01:10:43,380 --> 01:10:46,690
'The Cottage Hospital in Kingham - it's not
far.

1142
01:10:46,690 --> 01:10:50,350
I'll take you in the car, Mrs Taylor.'

1143
01:10:50,350 --> 01:10:55,640
Anna found a bandage in the First Aid box
and tied Mrs Taylor's arm up.

1144
01:10:55,640 --> 01:11:00,130
The poor old woman had gone a bit white now
and was shaking.

1145
01:11:00,130 --> 01:11:01,590
Someone passed her a cup of tea.

1146
01:11:01,590 --> 01:11:07,960
I was right, thought Anna, they came prepared
for anything!

1147
01:11:07,960 --> 01:11:13,280
By the time they reached Polreath, Mrs Taylor
looked better but her arm was clearly giving

1148
01:11:13,280 --> 01:11:15,659
her a lot of pain.

1149
01:11:15,659 --> 01:11:21,280
Fortunately, Tristan's car was near the harbour
and Mr and Mrs Taylor got in the back.

1150
01:11:21,280 --> 01:11:25,320
'Would you like me to come too?' asked Anna.

1151
01:11:25,320 --> 01:11:27,840
'Please,' said Tristan.

1152
01:11:27,840 --> 01:11:30,710
He looked more worried than anybody.

1153
01:11:30,710 --> 01:11:34,420
I wonder if he's insured for accidents, she
thought.

1154
01:11:34,420 --> 01:11:39,650
I suppose something like this is not good
for his business.

1155
01:11:39,650 --> 01:11:43,590
The X-ray showed bruising but the arm wasn't
broken.

1156
01:11:43,590 --> 01:11:48,530
'I'm really sorry, Mrs Taylor,' said Tristan.

1157
01:11:48,530 --> 01:11:51,530
'It's not your fault,' she replied.

1158
01:11:51,530 --> 01:11:54,139
'You're not responsible for the sea.

1159
01:11:54,139 --> 01:11:56,699
I shouldn't have been standing up.'

1160
01:11:56,699 --> 01:11:59,310
'Well, let's go back home.

1161
01:11:59,310 --> 01:12:01,830
I'll buy everyone a drink when we get back.

1162
01:12:01,830 --> 01:12:05,730
I think we all need one,' Tristan said.

1163
01:12:05,730 --> 01:12:11,280
The Taylors didn't want a drink, so Tristan
and Anna left them at their hotel.

1164
01:12:11,280 --> 01:12:14,570
'Your arm will hurt a lot tonight,' said Anna.

1165
01:12:14,570 --> 01:12:18,750
'So take some aspirins before you go to bed
- they'll help with the pain.'

1166
01:12:18,750 --> 01:12:22,409
'Thank you for your help,' said Mr Taylor.

1167
01:12:22,409 --> 01:12:26,210
'Well probably see you around somewhere in
the next day or two.'

1168
01:12:26,210 --> 01:12:31,280
'Poor old thing,' said Anna, drinking her
beer in the Fisherman's Arms.

1169
01:12:31,280 --> 01:12:33,260
'She was lucky today.

1170
01:12:33,260 --> 01:12:37,400
But I don't think she'll be doing much for
the next couple of days.

1171
01:12:37,400 --> 01:12:39,449
That arm'll hurt for a bit.'

1172
01:12:39,449 --> 01:12:44,120
'I was lucky,' replied Tristan, with a shake
of the head.

1173
01:12:44,120 --> 01:12:49,230
'It's fortunate she was so nice about it - someone
different might have complained and spread

1174
01:12:49,230 --> 01:12:51,159
the word about.

1175
01:12:51,159 --> 01:12:55,739
People would soon begin to think I was a bit
careless with my passengers, and there are

1176
01:12:55,739 --> 01:13:00,560
one or two people in this village who would
be quite happy to see me lose business.'

1177
01:13:00,560 --> 01:13:01,560
'Really?

1178
01:13:01,560 --> 01:13:02,560
Why?'

1179
01:13:02,560 --> 01:13:04,090
asked Anna.

1180
01:13:04,090 --> 01:13:08,880
'Oh, jealousy, I suppose,' Tristan replied.

1181
01:13:08,880 --> 01:13:13,540
'It's a small place, Polreath; feelings get
a bit strong sometimes.'

1182
01:13:13,540 --> 01:13:16,560
'Have they got reason to be jealous?'

1183
01:13:16,560 --> 01:13:21,040
Anna asked, remembering the conversation that
she and Stephen had heard in the bar the other

1184
01:13:21,040 --> 01:13:22,040
day.

1185
01:13:22,040 --> 01:13:27,120
'Well,' he laughed, 'I'm not sure I'm the
best person to answer that!

1186
01:13:27,120 --> 01:13:29,520
You should ask them!

1187
01:13:29,520 --> 01:13:34,750
People might think I've got a good life - what
with the boat and two cottages.'

1188
01:13:34,750 --> 01:13:37,389
'And maybe a third cottage to come?'

1189
01:13:37,389 --> 01:13:38,400
Anna added.

1190
01:13:38,400 --> 01:13:40,760
'Why do you say that?'

1191
01:13:40,760 --> 01:13:42,260
Tristan asked sharply.

1192
01:13:42,260 --> 01:13:44,760
'Sorry, I shouldn't have.

1193
01:13:44,760 --> 01:13:50,050
I was just repeating something we heard about
you in here the other day,' Anna said, wishing

1194
01:13:50,050 --> 01:13:51,440
she hadn't asked.

1195
01:13:51,440 --> 01:13:56,900
'A guy called Jack was saying that you were
interested in another cottage in the village.'

1196
01:13:56,900 --> 01:13:59,520
'Ah ha, Jack!

1197
01:13:59,520 --> 01:14:01,020
There you are, you see.

1198
01:14:01,020 --> 01:14:04,170
The stories that spread in a small village!'

1199
01:14:04,170 --> 01:14:05,679
Tristan looked a bit angry.

1200
01:14:05,679 --> 01:14:08,989
'Look, I'm sorry,' Anna said quickly.

1201
01:14:08,989 --> 01:14:11,050
'It's none of my business.

1202
01:14:11,050 --> 01:14:14,120
Shall we change the subject?

1203
01:14:14,120 --> 01:14:19,620
I meant to say earlier how much I enjoyed
the trip - except for the accident, of course.

1204
01:14:19,620 --> 01:14:22,850
You made it interesting for everyone.'

1205
01:14:22,850 --> 01:14:24,490
'Thanks.'

1206
01:14:24,490 --> 01:14:27,360
There was a bit of an uncomfortable silence.

1207
01:14:27,360 --> 01:14:32,489
Tristan stared into his beer and then said,
'I don't want another cottage.

1208
01:14:32,489 --> 01:14:38,199
I was interested in the price because it's
more or less the same size as Dolphin Cottage.

1209
01:14:38,199 --> 01:14:43,320
And I wanted to know how much I might be able
to sell that for.'

1210
01:14:43,320 --> 01:14:47,969
'You want to sell Dolphin Cottage?' said Anna
in complete surprise.

1211
01:14:47,969 --> 01:14:49,000
'Oh don't!

1212
01:14:49,000 --> 01:14:51,650
It's too lovely to lose.'

1213
01:14:51,650 --> 01:14:58,679
'I don't really know whether I want to or
not - I might need to, to get some money.

1214
01:14:58,679 --> 01:15:02,370
It's got some rather mixed memories for me
- Jill, you know.

1215
01:15:02,370 --> 01:15:07,980
And as you now understand, owning two places
can cause bad feeling.

1216
01:15:07,980 --> 01:15:10,420
'Anyway, I've got to go.

1217
01:15:10,420 --> 01:15:15,630
Believe it or not, I've got another trip to
do - a quick one-hour up the coast.'

1218
01:15:15,630 --> 01:15:18,540
He waited a second or two before continuing.

1219
01:15:18,540 --> 01:15:24,680
'But I was wondering, if you're not doing
anything tonight, can I buy you dinner - to

1220
01:15:24,680 --> 01:15:29,630
thank you for dinner last night, and for Mrs
Taylor?'

1221
01:15:29,630 --> 01:15:33,550
He looked at her carefully to see what she
would say.

1222
01:15:33,550 --> 01:15:37,889
Would she think he was just being friendly
or more than that?

1223
01:15:37,889 --> 01:15:42,750
He meant it to be friendly, but he had an
awful feeling he wanted more.

1224
01:15:42,750 --> 01:15:44,130
'Thank you.

1225
01:15:44,130 --> 01:15:48,060
I'd like that,' she said returning his look.

1226
01:15:48,060 --> 01:15:53,890
'I thought we could drive to a place in the
next village - it'd be a change.

1227
01:15:53,890 --> 01:15:56,200
Meet in the car park at eight?'

1228
01:15:56,200 --> 01:15:57,530
'Fine.

1229
01:15:57,530 --> 01:16:00,300
Have a safe trip this afternoon!'

1230
01:16:00,300 --> 01:16:06,840
She ordered a coffee and sat there, wondering
what she was doing, and feeling guilty because

1231
01:16:06,840 --> 01:16:13,220
she hadn't really thought about Stephen all
day.

1232
01:16:13,220 --> 01:16:14,840
CHAPTER NINE

1233
01:16:14,840 --> 01:16:15,920
Dinner at Gino's

1234
01:16:15,920 --> 01:16:23,840
'Someone's going to buy the company,' said
Stephen on the phone from London.

1235
01:16:23,840 --> 01:16:28,580
And then he said something about it being
'the best thing all round'.

1236
01:16:28,580 --> 01:16:33,370
He sounded quite cheerful, said he would be
with her in the morning and that he missed

1237
01:16:33,370 --> 01:16:34,830
her.

1238
01:16:34,830 --> 01:16:39,400
Anna felt, in all honesty, that she couldn't
say the same thing back to him.

1239
01:16:39,400 --> 01:16:45,520
Today had been so full of other things that
she hadn't really missed him.

1240
01:16:45,520 --> 01:16:51,719
So all she said to him was, 'It'll be lovely
to see you for breakfast' - which was true,

1241
01:16:51,719 --> 01:16:57,030
it would be lovely - Stephen was the most
important person in her life.

1242
01:16:57,030 --> 01:17:01,480
But she didn't say anything about going out
with Tristan.

1243
01:17:01,480 --> 01:17:06,840
She put on a bright red dress that she'd had
for years but which always made her feel great,

1244
01:17:06,840 --> 01:17:11,810
especially when she had a suntan, and gave
her hair a quick brush.

1245
01:17:11,810 --> 01:17:14,159
She was excited about tonight.

1246
01:17:14,159 --> 01:17:17,320
It was a great feeling getting ready to go
out with another man.

1247
01:17:17,320 --> 01:17:22,929
It reminded her of how she felt before she
met Stephen.

1248
01:17:22,929 --> 01:17:26,080
She walked slowly up the hill to the car park.

1249
01:17:26,080 --> 01:17:31,770
'Hey, you look nice,' said Anna when she saw
Tristan.

1250
01:17:31,770 --> 01:17:38,120
Instead of his usual shorts and T-shirt Tristan
was wearing trousers and a green short-sleeved

1251
01:17:38,120 --> 01:17:39,120
shirt.

1252
01:17:39,120 --> 01:17:41,920
'We're not going anywhere expensive, are we?'

1253
01:17:41,920 --> 01:17:43,239
she asked.

1254
01:17:43,239 --> 01:17:47,409
'No, just an Italian restaurant in St Leven,
not far.

1255
01:17:47,409 --> 01:17:49,820
And you look wonderful!'

1256
01:17:49,820 --> 01:17:50,840
Tristan replied.

1257
01:17:50,840 --> 01:17:53,659
'Shall we go?'

1258
01:17:53,659 --> 01:17:55,330
Tristan's car smelt of fish.

1259
01:17:55,330 --> 01:17:58,929
The whole of the back was full of nets.

1260
01:17:58,929 --> 01:18:03,280
'Does it smell?' he asked when he saw Anna's
face.

1261
01:18:03,280 --> 01:18:06,010
'It just seems normal to me.'

1262
01:18:06,010 --> 01:18:10,810
'Well, I'm just glad we're not going far,'
laughed Anna.

1263
01:18:10,810 --> 01:18:11,810
'Sorry.

1264
01:18:11,810 --> 01:18:14,560
Actually, all I can smell is your perfume.

1265
01:18:14,560 --> 01:18:18,530
Have you heard from Stephen?' asked Tristan.

1266
01:18:18,530 --> 01:18:21,389
'Yes, he just rang,' replied Anna.

1267
01:18:21,389 --> 01:18:23,150
'He seemed fine.

1268
01:18:23,150 --> 01:18:25,620
He said he'd be back tomorrow for breakfast.'

1269
01:18:25,620 --> 01:18:28,050
'Is he driving down overnight, then?' asked
Tristan.

1270
01:18:28,050 --> 01:18:30,409
'Yes, I guess so.

1271
01:18:30,409 --> 01:18:34,170
He likes night driving.'

1272
01:18:34,170 --> 01:18:37,570
It took about fifteen minutes to get to St
Leven.

1273
01:18:37,570 --> 01:18:41,620
Anna suggested going for a walk round the
harbour first.

1274
01:18:41,620 --> 01:18:45,530
She needed a bit of fresh air after the fishy
car.

1275
01:18:45,530 --> 01:18:50,469
The harbour was bigger than Polreath and so
were the fishing boats.

1276
01:18:50,469 --> 01:18:55,600
One or two of the men on board said hello
to Tristan and gave Anna a quick look.

1277
01:18:55,600 --> 01:19:00,020
'I get the feeling I'm being noticed,' Anna
thought.

1278
01:19:00,020 --> 01:19:06,310
'I wonder if that woman in the shop in Polreath
is going to tell me tomorrow what I was doing

1279
01:19:06,310 --> 01:19:07,310
tonight!'

1280
01:19:07,310 --> 01:19:11,090
'What are you smiling at?' asked Tristan.

1281
01:19:11,090 --> 01:19:17,560
'I was just thinking how hard it would be
to keep anything secret down here,' Anna replied.

1282
01:19:17,560 --> 01:19:18,920
'True.

1283
01:19:18,920 --> 01:19:23,500
Were you thinking about anything in particular?'
he asked, looking at her.

1284
01:19:23,500 --> 01:19:25,290
'No,' she lied.

1285
01:19:25,290 --> 01:19:26,920
'Let's go and eat.

1286
01:19:26,920 --> 01:19:29,949
I'm really hungry.'

1287
01:19:29,949 --> 01:19:34,590
Gino's restaurant was away from the sea, in
a narrow street.

1288
01:19:34,590 --> 01:19:38,420
They walked through the restaurant to the
garden at the back where there were a number

1289
01:19:38,420 --> 01:19:41,340
of tables gathered around a pizza oven.

1290
01:19:41,340 --> 01:19:46,580
Gino was putting in and taking out the pizzas
from the oven with a long wooden thing.

1291
01:19:46,580 --> 01:19:47,719
'Hello, Tristan.

1292
01:19:47,719 --> 01:19:50,000
Good to see you.

1293
01:19:50,000 --> 01:19:52,850
How are you?' said Gino.

1294
01:19:52,850 --> 01:19:57,530
Tristan and Anna sat at the only free table
and ordered two pizza margheritas and the

1295
01:19:57,530 --> 01:19:59,780
house wine.

1296
01:19:59,780 --> 01:20:04,730
They began talking about Italy, where they
had both been, and then the difficulty of

1297
01:20:04,730 --> 01:20:08,130
living away from your own country.

1298
01:20:08,130 --> 01:20:12,790
Tristan said it was not 'the country' that
was important for him but simply the place

1299
01:20:12,790 --> 01:20:15,580
where you were - the town, the village.

1300
01:20:15,580 --> 01:20:21,199
'And that's why Jill and I can never work
as a couple.

1301
01:20:21,199 --> 01:20:24,570
Neither of us is willing to leave the place
where we want to be.

1302
01:20:24,570 --> 01:20:30,600
We spoke on the phone earlier today and decided
to be realistic.

1303
01:20:30,600 --> 01:20:33,750
We haven't really got a future together.

1304
01:20:33,750 --> 01:20:36,080
I'm sure we'll try to remain friends.

1305
01:20:36,080 --> 01:20:40,880
There was a lot between us and we had good
laughs.

1306
01:20:40,880 --> 01:20:45,389
But everybody says that kind of thing when
their relationship breaks up.'

1307
01:20:45,389 --> 01:20:50,389
'I'm sorry it didn't work out for you,' said
Anna.

1308
01:20:50,389 --> 01:20:57,300
'Actually, you helped me to take the decision,'
said Tristan, and looked across at Anna to

1309
01:20:57,300 --> 01:20:59,790
see what she would do.

1310
01:20:59,790 --> 01:21:03,000
She was looking directly at him so he continued.

1311
01:21:03,000 --> 01:21:10,530
'This is going to sound like a Hollywood movie
but... you've woken me up.'

1312
01:21:10,530 --> 01:21:12,969
Tristan reached across the table and took
her hand.

1313
01:21:12,969 --> 01:21:18,179
'I was feeling really sorry for myself and
then you and Stephen arrived.'

1314
01:21:18,179 --> 01:21:23,030
'Yes, me and Stephen!

1315
01:21:23,030 --> 01:21:25,510
Anna repeated.

1316
01:21:25,510 --> 01:21:31,050
And yes, it did sound like a film, she thought,
but she wanted him to continue.

1317
01:21:31,050 --> 01:21:34,739
'What's so special about me and Stephen?

1318
01:21:34,739 --> 01:21:40,770
You must meet hundreds of visitors every year,
and they probably all fall in love with Polreath,

1319
01:21:40,770 --> 01:21:43,320
and half of them with you too.'

1320
01:21:43,320 --> 01:21:46,100
'I don't know why.

1321
01:21:46,100 --> 01:21:50,510
I just know I wanted to get to know you both
better.

1322
01:21:50,510 --> 01:21:54,010
Maybe you arrived at the right time, I don't
know.

1323
01:21:54,010 --> 01:21:59,159
Anyway, whatever it is, I feel clearer about
some things.'

1324
01:21:59,159 --> 01:22:01,960
'I don't,' thought Anna.

1325
01:22:01,960 --> 01:22:03,480
'I feel confused.

1326
01:22:03,480 --> 01:22:07,300
Why is he holding my hand?

1327
01:22:07,300 --> 01:22:11,050
Would he be holding Stephen's hand too if
he was here?'

1328
01:22:11,050 --> 01:22:15,000
'But now there's another problem,' he went
on.

1329
01:22:15,000 --> 01:22:18,469
'I think we're attracted to one another.'

1330
01:22:18,469 --> 01:22:20,330
Anna pulled her hand away.

1331
01:22:20,330 --> 01:22:22,699
How could he say that!

1332
01:22:22,699 --> 01:22:27,920
He'd just been talking about her and Stephen
and now he was saying this.

1333
01:22:27,920 --> 01:22:29,420
How could he?

1334
01:22:29,420 --> 01:22:32,870
Five minutes ago, he'd been talking about
breaking up with Jill.

1335
01:22:32,870 --> 01:22:35,300
That can't have been easy to do.

1336
01:22:35,300 --> 01:22:39,230
And here he was, saying he was attracted to
her.

1337
01:22:39,230 --> 01:22:44,679
It sounded like throwing off one pair of shoes
and trying on a new pair.

1338
01:22:44,679 --> 01:22:46,830
What was he doing?

1339
01:22:46,830 --> 01:22:47,900
'I'm sorry.

1340
01:22:47,900 --> 01:22:49,650
I shouldn't have said that.'

1341
01:22:49,650 --> 01:22:51,860
'No, you shouldn't,' said Anna.

1342
01:22:51,860 --> 01:22:54,950
'But it's true, isn't it?'

1343
01:22:54,950 --> 01:22:57,250
Tristan said softly.

1344
01:22:57,250 --> 01:22:59,370
'Yes.'

1345
01:22:59,370 --> 01:23:03,200
And she picked up her glass to hide her confusion.

1346
01:23:03,200 --> 01:23:06,480
'But I don't intend to do anything about it.

1347
01:23:06,480 --> 01:23:10,350
I'm with Stephen and we're happy.

1348
01:23:10,350 --> 01:23:12,130
And you've confused me.'

1349
01:23:12,130 --> 01:23:15,469
'Same here,' he said.

1350
01:23:15,469 --> 01:23:17,400
He took hold of her hand again.

1351
01:23:17,400 --> 01:23:23,240
'I know you're happy with Stephen - I could
see it the first day you were here.

1352
01:23:23,240 --> 01:23:28,700
I just thought it was better to bring everything
out into the open.

1353
01:23:28,700 --> 01:23:33,700
Sometimes if you don't talk about things they
become even more important.'

1354
01:23:33,700 --> 01:23:37,960
'Maybe some things are better left unsaid.

1355
01:23:37,960 --> 01:23:43,400
Stephen's coming back tomorrow and in three
weeks I'll have disappeared out of your life.

1356
01:23:43,400 --> 01:23:48,170
Oh, I don't know what I'm doing anymore,'
Anna said.

1357
01:23:48,170 --> 01:23:51,650
'It's not a crime to find someone attractive,
is it?' he said.

1358
01:23:51,650 --> 01:23:53,310
'No, it's not.

1359
01:23:53,310 --> 01:23:57,110
In fact, it's great in a way.

1360
01:23:57,110 --> 01:24:02,190
But I've been with Stephen for ten years and
this is the first time I've been in this situation.

1361
01:24:02,190 --> 01:24:05,360
I don't know what to do.

1362
01:24:05,360 --> 01:24:09,300
And by the way, Gino is looking at us.

1363
01:24:09,300 --> 01:24:12,250
Let's talk about something else, please.'

1364
01:24:12,250 --> 01:24:13,880
And they did.

1365
01:24:13,880 --> 01:24:17,230
They talked about food and they slowly relaxed.

1366
01:24:17,230 --> 01:24:20,860
But all the time Anna was thinking.

1367
01:24:20,860 --> 01:24:28,239
She did find him attractive and if there were
no Stephen, who knows what might happen.

1368
01:24:28,239 --> 01:24:31,660
Recently she had felt excluded sometimes by
Stephen.

1369
01:24:31,660 --> 01:24:36,750
He had seemed to be in a world of his own,
so it was wonderful to be the centre of Tristan's

1370
01:24:36,750 --> 01:24:39,680
attention.

1371
01:24:39,680 --> 01:24:42,850
Tristan's thoughts were going along similar
lines.

1372
01:24:42,850 --> 01:24:45,389
He didn't want to hurt anybody.

1373
01:24:45,389 --> 01:24:47,990
Maybe he should have kept his mouth shut.

1374
01:24:47,990 --> 01:24:53,090
That was his problem - he always had to say
what he was thinking, didn't he?

1375
01:24:53,090 --> 01:24:57,350
It had got him into trouble more than once
in the past.

1376
01:24:57,350 --> 01:25:02,699
Anna was a warm, open, lively woman - and
he felt good when he was with her.

1377
01:25:02,699 --> 01:25:08,250
But, as she said, she would be leaving in
three weeks, so there was no point in letting

1378
01:25:08,250 --> 01:25:10,940
things go any further.

1379
01:25:10,940 --> 01:25:13,780
They got up to leave and Gino came over.

1380
01:25:13,780 --> 01:25:19,570
'Cheerio, my friend,' he said, and my friend's
friend,' he said looking at Anna.

1381
01:25:19,570 --> 01:25:21,670
'Hope to see you again.

1382
01:25:21,670 --> 01:25:23,100
Be good!'

1383
01:25:23,100 --> 01:25:30,230
'Mmm, an interesting choice of words,' thought
Tristan as they stepped out into the street.

1384
01:25:30,230 --> 01:25:36,090
'Gosh, Tristan, the smell of fish in your
car is quite powerful.

1385
01:25:36,090 --> 01:25:40,290
We'll have to drive with the windows open,'
said Anna.

1386
01:25:40,290 --> 01:25:44,450
Sitting in the car on the way back to Polreath
was not very easy.

1387
01:25:44,450 --> 01:25:47,940
And it wasn't just because of the fishy smell.

1388
01:25:47,940 --> 01:25:52,090
They were both very conscious of each other
sitting close by.

1389
01:25:52,090 --> 01:25:55,880
Tristan parked the car above the village and
they got out.

1390
01:25:55,880 --> 01:25:58,400
'Let's just walk for a bit,' said Anna.

1391
01:25:58,400 --> 01:26:01,630
'I don't want to go back to the cottage yet.'

1392
01:26:01,630 --> 01:26:05,760
They took the path along the top of the cliffs.

1393
01:26:05,760 --> 01:26:10,280
It was dark but the moon was bright enough
so there was no danger of them walking over

1394
01:26:10,280 --> 01:26:11,869
the edge.

1395
01:26:11,869 --> 01:26:17,150
In places, the path was quite narrow where
it passed between bushes and Anna walked in

1396
01:26:17,150 --> 01:26:18,690
front.

1397
01:26:18,690 --> 01:26:23,250
Being in front made her feel as if she was
in charge of the situation.

1398
01:26:23,250 --> 01:26:29,420
Then she heard something move just ahead,
an animal probably, and she stopped suddenly.

1399
01:26:29,420 --> 01:26:31,480
Tristan walked into the back of her.

1400
01:26:31,480 --> 01:26:33,550
She jumped and half turned round.

1401
01:26:33,550 --> 01:26:37,690
They were standing so close.

1402
01:26:37,690 --> 01:26:40,510
She reached up and touched his face with her
finger.

1403
01:26:40,510 --> 01:26:46,420
He put his arms round her and they kissed,
long and hard.

1404
01:26:46,420 --> 01:26:49,199
Anna pulled away from him.

1405
01:26:49,199 --> 01:26:55,159
'So much for not letting things go any further,'
said Tristan softly.

1406
01:26:55,159 --> 01:26:59,150
'I think I knew that was going to happen,'
said Anna.

1407
01:26:59,150 --> 01:27:02,219
The sense of his body was still with her.

1408
01:27:02,219 --> 01:27:08,180
'I know this might sound odd, but I needed
that!'

1409
01:27:08,180 --> 01:27:09,230
Tristan smiled.

1410
01:27:09,230 --> 01:27:14,180
'So did I - and I need more.'

1411
01:27:14,180 --> 01:27:18,260
They kissed again but this time more lightly.

1412
01:27:18,260 --> 01:27:23,469
It was almost as if a spell had been broken,
and a deep and exciting kiss had been enough

1413
01:27:23,469 --> 01:27:24,680
for the moment.

1414
01:27:24,680 --> 01:27:29,730
'Anna, I think you're wonderful,' he said,
trying to keep his voice light.

1415
01:27:29,730 --> 01:27:35,170
'I wish we were free to do whatever we want,
but we're not.

1416
01:27:35,170 --> 01:27:39,670
At least, I'll still be able to look Stephen
in the eye when I see him tomorrow.'

1417
01:27:39,670 --> 01:27:42,119
'I hope I can, too.

1418
01:27:42,119 --> 01:27:46,619
Do you think we'd better go before anything
else happens?

1419
01:27:46,619 --> 01:27:51,429
We don't need to say anything to Stephen,
either of us, do we?'

1420
01:27:51,429 --> 01:27:55,130
'No, why should we?' he replied.

1421
01:27:55,130 --> 01:27:57,280
'Nothing's happened.'

1422
01:27:57,280 --> 01:28:04,800
But they both knew something had.

1423
01:28:04,800 --> 01:28:06,420
CHAPTER TEN

1424
01:28:06,420 --> 01:28:10,530
Stephen's return

1425
01:28:10,530 --> 01:28:14,290
Anna woke up because she felt something on
her cheek.

1426
01:28:14,290 --> 01:28:15,619
She pushed it away.

1427
01:28:15,619 --> 01:28:16,619
'Ouch!

1428
01:28:16,619 --> 01:28:18,860
That's my nose!'

1429
01:28:18,860 --> 01:28:20,590
Stephen cried.

1430
01:28:20,590 --> 01:28:25,820
She opened her eyes and there was Stephen
bending over her and rubbing his nose where

1431
01:28:25,820 --> 01:28:27,600
she'd hit it.

1432
01:28:27,600 --> 01:28:31,320
'Hello, love,' said Anna.

1433
01:28:31,320 --> 01:28:33,380
'You're back.

1434
01:28:33,380 --> 01:28:35,060
What time is it?'

1435
01:28:35,060 --> 01:28:36,060
'Seven.

1436
01:28:36,060 --> 01:28:41,070
Sorry to wake you but you looked so lovely
lying there.

1437
01:28:41,070 --> 01:28:43,469
I'll go and make some coffee and bring it
up.

1438
01:28:43,469 --> 01:28:45,780
It's a beautiful morning.'

1439
01:28:45,780 --> 01:28:52,040
Anna lay there, listening to Stephen downstairs,
and remembering the night before.

1440
01:28:52,040 --> 01:28:54,929
She felt good.

1441
01:28:54,929 --> 01:28:58,980
She'd had an 'adventure' and she had escaped.

1442
01:28:58,980 --> 01:29:04,060
Now Stephen was back and everything would
be back to normal.

1443
01:29:04,060 --> 01:29:09,680
He sat on the bed drinking coffee and told
her about the agency meeting.

1444
01:29:09,680 --> 01:29:14,270
Everyone had all agreed in the end that the
sale of the company was the best thing.

1445
01:29:14,270 --> 01:29:18,889
The buyers had been honest about the future
and said there were no guarantees of people

1446
01:29:18,889 --> 01:29:20,250
keeping their jobs.

1447
01:29:20,250 --> 01:29:25,070
There would have to be some restructuring
- which, according to Stephen, meant a lot

1448
01:29:25,070 --> 01:29:27,820
of people losing their jobs.

1449
01:29:27,820 --> 01:29:33,380
'So, we're going to have a few months without
knowing whether I'll be one of the lucky ones,'

1450
01:29:33,380 --> 01:29:34,860
said Stephen.

1451
01:29:34,860 --> 01:29:39,250
'Well, you look very cheerful about it,' replied
Anna.

1452
01:29:39,250 --> 01:29:40,929
'There's nothing I can do.

1453
01:29:40,929 --> 01:29:42,429
It's out of my hands.

1454
01:29:42,429 --> 01:29:44,980
So to hell with it all, for the moment.

1455
01:29:44,980 --> 01:29:49,820
I don't even know if I want to keep the job
anyway,' Stephen said as he started to get

1456
01:29:49,820 --> 01:29:50,820
undressed.

1457
01:29:50,820 --> 01:29:56,510
'I'm going to have a shower, and then maybe
have a few hours' sleep.'

1458
01:29:56,510 --> 01:29:58,640
Anna was surprised.

1459
01:29:58,640 --> 01:30:01,090
Stephen didn't really seem worried about it
all.

1460
01:30:01,090 --> 01:30:02,360
'How amazing!

1461
01:30:02,360 --> 01:30:06,640
Perhaps he is changing,' she thought.

1462
01:30:06,640 --> 01:30:08,760
She decided to get up.

1463
01:30:08,760 --> 01:30:12,290
She didn't feel like lying in bed waiting
for Stephen.

1464
01:30:12,290 --> 01:30:14,790
It was better to be active.

1465
01:30:14,790 --> 01:30:20,920
She made another cup of coffee and stood outside
listening to the morning sounds.

1466
01:30:20,920 --> 01:30:25,690
Tristan was on his boat, doing something with
a fishing net.

1467
01:30:25,690 --> 01:30:28,969
'Probably one of the smelly ones from the
car,' she thought.

1468
01:30:28,969 --> 01:30:33,950
How did she feel about him this morning?

1469
01:30:33,950 --> 01:30:38,909
Quite relaxed, she thought, although something
was making her heart beat faster.

1470
01:30:38,909 --> 01:30:46,469
'Must be the coffee,' she said to herself,
and went inside to get some breakfast.

1471
01:30:46,469 --> 01:30:48,969
'Did you have a good evening with Tristan?'

1472
01:30:48,969 --> 01:30:51,280
Stephen was sitting at the kitchen table.

1473
01:30:51,280 --> 01:30:53,969
He stood up and put his arms round Anna.

1474
01:30:53,969 --> 01:31:01,150
'Mm, yes, I did,' said Anna, wondering for
a moment which evening he was talking about.

1475
01:31:01,150 --> 01:31:03,050
'Yes, it was fun.

1476
01:31:03,050 --> 01:31:08,240
He's very good to be with - and very open
about everything, isn't he?

1477
01:31:08,240 --> 01:31:11,710
It doesn't seem to worry him that he's only
just met us.

1478
01:31:11,710 --> 01:31:17,730
Anyway, what are you doing - I thought you
were going to have a bit of sleep?'

1479
01:31:17,730 --> 01:31:20,300
'Changed my mind,' replied Stephen.

1480
01:31:20,300 --> 01:31:24,969
'The bed seemed empty, and I don't want to
waste the day sleeping.

1481
01:31:24,969 --> 01:31:27,190
I want to start my holiday again.

1482
01:31:27,190 --> 01:31:30,090
Do you feel like going surfing later?

1483
01:31:30,090 --> 01:31:35,790
If we walk over there, you can tell me what
you've been doing while I've been away.'

1484
01:31:35,790 --> 01:31:40,590
Anna had already decided that she was going
to tell him about last night's dinner.

1485
01:31:40,590 --> 01:31:46,380
She knew if she didn't, he was sure to hear
about it from someone else - half the population

1486
01:31:46,380 --> 01:31:49,150
of Polreath and St Leven probably.

1487
01:31:49,150 --> 01:31:54,139
So, as they walked over to the surf beach,
she told him all about going on the boat out

1488
01:31:54,139 --> 01:32:00,750
to the rocks, and the accident and about Gino's,
and even about Tristan and Jill splitting

1489
01:32:00,750 --> 01:32:02,150
up.

1490
01:32:02,150 --> 01:32:05,440
But she missed out the walk at the end of
the evening.

1491
01:32:05,440 --> 01:32:09,360
She could feel Stephen looking at her once
or twice.

1492
01:32:09,360 --> 01:32:13,350
'Well, you have been busy,' he said thoughtfully.

1493
01:32:13,350 --> 01:32:16,080
She seemed to have been perfectly happy without
him.

1494
01:32:16,080 --> 01:32:19,420
'You obviously enjoyed it all.

1495
01:32:19,420 --> 01:32:21,210
You like Tristan, don't you?'

1496
01:32:21,210 --> 01:32:23,929
'Yes - don't you?'

1497
01:32:23,929 --> 01:32:25,530
she replied.

1498
01:32:25,530 --> 01:32:30,900
'Yes, at least, what I know of him,' said
Stephen slowly.

1499
01:32:30,900 --> 01:32:36,320
'I like the way he lives and the way he seems
to know what makes him happy.

1500
01:32:36,320 --> 01:32:39,010
That's quite rare.'

1501
01:32:39,010 --> 01:32:42,730
Anna waited; she realised that Stephen hadn't
finished.

1502
01:32:42,730 --> 01:32:49,280
'Did he tell you he went to university - he
got a degree in civil engineering?

1503
01:32:49,280 --> 01:32:52,760
He was offered a good job, too, but he didn't
take it.

1504
01:32:52,760 --> 01:32:55,409
He wanted to come back to Polreath instead.

1505
01:32:55,409 --> 01:33:01,350
He could have been really successful by now
- probably a manager with a high salary.

1506
01:33:01,350 --> 01:33:05,290
But he knew that wasn't really for him,' Stephen
paused.

1507
01:33:05,290 --> 01:33:08,940
Now it was Anna's turn to look at him.

1508
01:33:08,940 --> 01:33:13,420
'What are you saying?' asked Anna.

1509
01:33:13,420 --> 01:33:20,020
'Nothing really - just that I think he made
the right decision - for him,' Stephen said.

1510
01:33:20,020 --> 01:33:25,090
'Are you trying to tell me you feel you've
made the wrong decision?

1511
01:33:25,090 --> 01:33:30,630
I always thought you loved the advertising
world - and life in the city,' said Anna.

1512
01:33:30,630 --> 01:33:32,320
'I do...

1513
01:33:32,320 --> 01:33:34,020
I did.'

1514
01:33:34,020 --> 01:33:35,949
Stephen stopped for a moment.

1515
01:33:35,949 --> 01:33:40,600
All I'm saying is I think I've reached a crossroads
in my life.

1516
01:33:40,600 --> 01:33:43,840
I feel it's time for a change of direction.

1517
01:33:43,840 --> 01:33:46,980
Maybe it's a mid-life crisis - I don't know.'

1518
01:33:46,980 --> 01:33:50,870
'You're too young for a mid-life crisis,'
replied Anna.

1519
01:33:50,870 --> 01:33:54,920
'Have you got any ideas about what you'd like
to do, then?'

1520
01:33:54,920 --> 01:34:00,619
'One or two but they're still just ideas,
so I don't really want to talk about them

1521
01:34:00,619 --> 01:34:01,619
yet.'

1522
01:34:01,619 --> 01:34:04,889
'I've heard that before,' thought Anna.

1523
01:34:04,889 --> 01:34:08,989
Stephen continued, 'I need time to think more.

1524
01:34:08,989 --> 01:34:10,060
Everything's happened so quickly'

1525
01:34:10,060 --> 01:34:13,460
'Not that quickly, actually,' she said.

1526
01:34:13,460 --> 01:34:17,000
'You've seemed different the last few weeks.

1527
01:34:17,000 --> 01:34:19,989
I think this has been coming for a while.'

1528
01:34:19,989 --> 01:34:21,659
'You're probably right.

1529
01:34:21,659 --> 01:34:24,420
But don't push me to say more at the moment,
will you?

1530
01:34:24,420 --> 01:34:27,090
I need time.'

1531
01:34:27,090 --> 01:34:31,500
They walked on in silence, busy with their
own thoughts.

1532
01:34:31,500 --> 01:34:34,739
Anna wasn't surprised by what Stephen had
said.

1533
01:34:34,739 --> 01:34:39,130
She just hoped he'd talk to her more before
taking any big decisions.

1534
01:34:39,130 --> 01:34:43,960
After all, it affected her life, too.

1535
01:34:43,960 --> 01:34:46,949
The surf beach was busy when they got there.

1536
01:34:46,949 --> 01:34:53,320
'I'm ready for this,' said Stephen, 'after
the last forty-eight hours, I need action.'

1537
01:34:53,320 --> 01:34:57,030
They went to the beach shop and hired surfboards.

1538
01:34:57,030 --> 01:35:01,000
Neither of them felt like having a lesson
- they wanted to try it themselves first.

1539
01:35:01,000 --> 01:35:06,389
They swam out with the boards to just beyond
the point where the waves were starting.

1540
01:35:06,389 --> 01:35:09,699
Then they watched to see what other people
did.

1541
01:35:09,699 --> 01:35:11,949
Timing was the important thing.

1542
01:35:11,949 --> 01:35:15,540
You had to catch the right wave at exactly
the right time.

1543
01:35:15,540 --> 01:35:19,640
If you missed it, there was nothing to carry
you in towards the beach.

1544
01:35:19,640 --> 01:35:22,850
You had to try again, wait for the next suitable
wave.

1545
01:35:22,850 --> 01:35:24,040
It was fun.

1546
01:35:24,040 --> 01:35:28,290
They couldn't really do it well, but they
enjoyed trying.

1547
01:35:28,290 --> 01:35:33,360
Stephen did manage to stand up on his board
for about ten seconds but Anna was perfectly

1548
01:35:33,360 --> 01:35:37,199
happy lying down on the board, surfing in
on her stomach.

1549
01:35:37,199 --> 01:35:40,250
'I've had enough,' shouted Anna.

1550
01:35:40,250 --> 01:35:43,909
'I'm giving up for the moment.'

1551
01:35:43,909 --> 01:35:47,219
She lay on the sand and let the sun warm her.

1552
01:35:47,219 --> 01:35:49,190
Then she sat up to watch Stephen.

1553
01:35:49,190 --> 01:35:51,790
He was doing quite well.

1554
01:35:51,790 --> 01:35:54,619
But then he often did do well at sport.

1555
01:35:54,619 --> 01:35:56,970
She could see he wanted to be good at this.

1556
01:35:56,970 --> 01:36:02,360
'I enjoyed that,' said Stephen, lying down
on the beach beside her.

1557
01:36:02,360 --> 01:36:06,969
'When you get it right, it's a great feeling!'

1558
01:36:06,969 --> 01:36:10,560
Turning over, he put his cold, wet hands on
Anna's stomach.

1559
01:36:10,560 --> 01:36:11,560
'Ohhhh!

1560
01:36:11,560 --> 01:36:12,810
You horror!

1561
01:36:12,810 --> 01:36:15,810
Your hands are freezing!'

1562
01:36:15,810 --> 01:36:18,900
He laughed, and pulled her to her feet.

1563
01:36:18,900 --> 01:36:20,340
'Time for lunch.

1564
01:36:20,340 --> 01:36:23,280
I could eat a horse.'

1565
01:36:23,280 --> 01:36:28,370
They carried their surfboards to the open-air
cafe and 'parked' them next to some others.

1566
01:36:28,370 --> 01:36:33,790
They had burgers and French fries with lots
of ketchup, and enjoyed every mouthful of

1567
01:36:33,790 --> 01:36:34,790
it.

1568
01:36:34,790 --> 01:36:40,110
'God, that was wonderful - just what I needed,'
said Stephen.

1569
01:36:40,110 --> 01:36:41,580
'OK.

1570
01:36:41,580 --> 01:36:43,350
What do you want to do now, then?

1571
01:36:43,350 --> 01:36:45,750
I'd quite like to go back to the cottage.

1572
01:36:45,750 --> 01:36:47,980
