too.'

1577
01:37:05,230 --> 01:37:07,000
CHAPTER ELEVEN

1578
01:37:07,000 --> 01:37:10,030
Back to normal

1579
01:37:10,030 --> 01:37:13,350
Stephen went upstairs for a rest when they
got home.

1580
01:37:13,350 --> 01:37:16,699
He asked Anna to wake him in a couple of hours.

1581
01:37:16,699 --> 01:37:23,920
She took her coffee, newspaper, book and suntan
cream into the garden and made herself comfortable.

1582
01:37:23,920 --> 01:37:26,690
The sun felt good on her skin.

1583
01:37:26,690 --> 01:37:32,030
She felt totally happy and couldn't imagine
ever wanting anything more.

1584
01:37:32,030 --> 01:37:37,530
'It'd probably be better,' she thought, 'if
we didn't see Tristan today.

1585
01:37:37,530 --> 01:37:41,199
Just give me time to get myself in balance
again.

1586
01:37:41,199 --> 01:37:46,250
It seems as if that man is having an interesting
effect on both Stephen and me.

1587
01:37:46,250 --> 01:37:51,840
I think Stephen knows I'm attracted to him,
and Stephen obviously likes him too.'

1588
01:37:51,840 --> 01:37:57,210
At about five o'clock, she took a cup of tea
to Stephen to wake him up.

1589
01:37:57,210 --> 01:37:59,990
He was fast asleep.

1590
01:37:59,990 --> 01:38:02,110
'Teatime,' she whispered in his ear.

1591
01:38:02,110 --> 01:38:06,950
He opened one eye and stared at her standing
there in her swimsuit.

1592
01:38:06,950 --> 01:38:12,200
'How nice to be woken up by a half-naked woman
with a cup of tea.

1593
01:38:12,200 --> 01:38:17,219
Why don't you join me in here, it's lovely.'

1594
01:38:17,219 --> 01:38:20,030
She got in and they made love.

1595
01:38:20,030 --> 01:38:26,250
They knew each other so well - it was all
so familiar, not passionate but comfortable

1596
01:38:26,250 --> 01:38:28,790
and loving.

1597
01:38:28,790 --> 01:38:31,890
'I'd like to stay here forever,' said Stephen.

1598
01:38:31,890 --> 01:38:34,100
'What, in bed?'

1599
01:38:34,100 --> 01:38:37,790
'No, in Polreath,' he laughed.

1600
01:38:37,790 --> 01:38:45,980
'It suits us both - you look wonderful and
I feel better than I have for months.'

1601
01:38:45,980 --> 01:38:49,380
'You said the same last year when we were
in Greece - remember?'

1602
01:38:49,380 --> 01:38:53,130
'Did I?' said Stephen, getting out of bed.

1603
01:38:53,130 --> 01:38:58,700
'Oh well, this is different, I think.'

1604
01:38:58,700 --> 01:39:03,830
It was late afternoon and they went down to
the beach for a lazy swim.

1605
01:39:03,830 --> 01:39:09,389
They called at the shop and sure enough, the
woman said, 'What did you think of Gino's

1606
01:39:09,389 --> 01:39:10,850
then, Mrs Martins?'

1607
01:39:10,850 --> 01:39:15,949
'I knew it,' thought Anna, 'I knew she would
say something.

1608
01:39:15,949 --> 01:39:21,060
It's a good thing I told Stephen or I'd be
in trouble now.'

1609
01:39:21,060 --> 01:39:25,280
She answered the woman in her sweetest voice.

1610
01:39:25,280 --> 01:39:28,630
Outside the shop, Stephen suggested going
for a drink.

1611
01:39:28,630 --> 01:39:31,900
'No, let's go back home.'

1612
01:39:31,900 --> 01:39:35,320
Anna was surprised to find she felt bad about
the woman's comments.

1613
01:39:35,320 --> 01:39:40,690
In any case, she didn't think she wanted to
meet Tristan at the moment.

1614
01:39:40,690 --> 01:39:43,940
They spent a pleasant evening at home.

1615
01:39:43,940 --> 01:39:49,030
Stephen cooked an amazing fish pie, and they
ate outside even though the evening was not

1616
01:39:49,030 --> 01:39:51,280
quite as warm as before.

1617
01:39:51,280 --> 01:39:54,110
'I'd like a quick beer in the pub before bedtime.

1618
01:39:54,110 --> 01:39:55,349
Do you want to come?' asked Stephen.

1619
01:39:55,349 --> 01:39:59,250
'No, I'll stay here.

1620
01:39:59,250 --> 01:40:01,909
You won't be long, will you?'

1621
01:40:01,909 --> 01:40:05,110
Ten minutes after Stephen left, the phone
rang.

1622
01:40:05,110 --> 01:40:11,880
'If that's anybody from London from Stephen's
office, I'll probably shout at them,' thought

1623
01:40:11,880 --> 01:40:13,290
Anna as she stood up.

1624
01:40:13,290 --> 01:40:16,500
'Why don't they leave him alone?'

1625
01:40:16,500 --> 01:40:17,500
'Hello!'

1626
01:40:17,500 --> 01:40:18,670
she said very roughly.

1627
01:40:18,670 --> 01:40:19,719
'Hello.

1628
01:40:19,719 --> 01:40:22,489
God, you sound angry!'

1629
01:40:22,489 --> 01:40:23,920
It was Tristan.

1630
01:40:23,920 --> 01:40:26,469
'Oh hello, Tristan.

1631
01:40:26,469 --> 01:40:29,780
Sorry, I thought it was going to be someone
else.

1632
01:40:29,780 --> 01:40:30,780
Sorry.

1633
01:40:30,780 --> 01:40:31,780
What...

1634
01:40:31,780 --> 01:40:33,739
I mean, why...?'

1635
01:40:33,739 --> 01:40:36,280
and she didn't know how to finish.

1636
01:40:36,280 --> 01:40:38,969
'You mean why am I ringing?'

1637
01:40:38,969 --> 01:40:40,860
Tristan finished her question for her.

1638
01:40:40,860 --> 01:40:47,360
'Well, I saw Stephen going into the Fisherman's
Arms so I thought I'd just check to see if

1639
01:40:47,360 --> 01:40:49,790
you... if everything's OK.'

1640
01:40:49,790 --> 01:40:53,820
'Yes, I think so,' she said.

1641
01:40:53,820 --> 01:40:55,030
'Stephen's happy to be back.

1642
01:40:55,030 --> 01:41:00,270
In fact, I thought when the phone rang it
was going to be someone about his work - that's

1643
01:41:00,270 --> 01:41:01,730
why I sounded angry.

1644
01:41:01,730 --> 01:41:04,810
Is everything OK with you?'

1645
01:41:04,810 --> 01:41:06,040
'Yes, fine.'

1646
01:41:06,040 --> 01:41:07,270
A pause.

1647
01:41:07,270 --> 01:41:12,380
'The other reason I rang was to remind you
that there's another trip to Skellig tomorrow

1648
01:41:12,380 --> 01:41:13,940
morning if you're interested.

1649
01:41:13,940 --> 01:41:18,880
It'd be nice to see you, both of you, I think.'

1650
01:41:18,880 --> 01:41:22,260
Tristan sounded a bit embarrassed.

1651
01:41:22,260 --> 01:41:23,260
'Right.

1652
01:41:23,260 --> 01:41:27,160
We'll probably come - I'll mention it to Stephen
when he gets back.

1653
01:41:27,160 --> 01:41:30,590
What's the weather forecast for tomorrow?'
asked Anna.

1654
01:41:30,590 --> 01:41:33,400
'I thought it was a bit cooler tonight.

1655
01:41:33,400 --> 01:41:35,860
It's not going to change, is it?'

1656
01:41:35,860 --> 01:41:37,810
'No, not yet,' he replied.

1657
01:41:37,810 --> 01:41:41,460
'We've got the good weather for a bit longer,
so they say.'

1658
01:41:41,460 --> 01:41:43,400
'Look, Tristan.

1659
01:41:43,400 --> 01:41:46,800
Why don't you go and join Stephen in the bar?

1660
01:41:46,800 --> 01:41:51,730
He'd like to see you, I know, and it might
be a good idea to see him without me around

1661
01:41:51,730 --> 01:41:54,140
for the first time since we...

1662
01:41:54,140 --> 01:41:57,830
you know...' and again, Anna couldn't finish.

1663
01:41:57,830 --> 01:42:02,969
'Mm, that's probably a good idea,' said Tristan
brightly.

1664
01:42:02,969 --> 01:42:03,989
'Thanks.

1665
01:42:03,989 --> 01:42:06,580
I won't say anything about ringing you tonight.

1666
01:42:06,580 --> 01:42:09,320
And I'll mention the trip to Skellig to him.

1667
01:42:09,320 --> 01:42:10,320
OK?

1668
01:42:10,320 --> 01:42:11,400
Goodnight, Anna.

1669
01:42:11,400 --> 01:42:14,670
See you tomorrow, I hope.'

1670
01:42:14,670 --> 01:42:19,590
Anna was pleased with herself for being so
strong-minded, but she was shaking a bit when

1671
01:42:19,590 --> 01:42:21,760
she put the phone down.

1672
01:42:21,760 --> 01:42:24,390
Then she thought it was quite funny, really.

1673
01:42:24,390 --> 01:42:27,850
Last night with her - tonight with Stephen.

1674
01:42:27,850 --> 01:42:32,240
Tristan was certainly being very equal in
sharing himself between them.

1675
01:42:32,240 --> 01:42:40,750
She hoped the woman from the shop would see
them together!

1676
01:42:40,750 --> 01:42:41,770
CHAPTER TWELVE

1677
01:42:41,770 --> 01:42:45,580
Decision time

1678
01:42:45,580 --> 01:42:49,890
The next day they went on Tristans trip to
Skellig.

1679
01:42:49,890 --> 01:42:54,940
About fifty people lived on the island all
year, and there was one hotel and a few holiday

1680
01:42:54,940 --> 01:42:56,830
cottages.

1681
01:42:56,830 --> 01:43:01,920
It took them about an hour to walk around
the island, which, as Tristan had said, did

1682
01:43:01,920 --> 01:43:05,320
seem to have something special about it.

1683
01:43:05,320 --> 01:43:08,570
It was difficult to say exactly what it was.

1684
01:43:08,570 --> 01:43:11,139
Maybe all small islands had it.

1685
01:43:11,139 --> 01:43:14,699
The far side, away from the coast, was the
best.

1686
01:43:14,699 --> 01:43:20,320
There was nothing to be seen except the rocks
where Anna had been a few days ago.

1687
01:43:20,320 --> 01:43:24,750
Just ocean, going on forever.

1688
01:43:24,750 --> 01:43:29,230
After their walk, they sat on the beach and
discussed whether they could live there.

1689
01:43:29,230 --> 01:43:33,900
This was a game they often played when they
went somewhere new.

1690
01:43:33,900 --> 01:43:39,760
Stephen thought he could, if he had some work
to do, but Anna didn't think she'd like it.

1691
01:43:39,760 --> 01:43:45,599
'I'd be worried, I might not like any of the
other forty-eight people living here.

1692
01:43:45,599 --> 01:43:49,830
It's not many to choose from,' she said.

1693
01:43:49,830 --> 01:43:54,530
About half an hour before the boat was leaving,
they saw Tristan walking over the beach towards

1694
01:43:54,530 --> 01:43:56,260
them.

1695
01:43:56,260 --> 01:44:00,969
'It's a beautiful place, isn't it?' said Tristan,
sitting down with them.

1696
01:44:00,969 --> 01:44:04,139
'Yes,' replied Stephen.

1697
01:44:04,139 --> 01:44:08,840
'Stephen thinks he could live here,' said
Anna, 'but I'm quite sure I couldn't.'

1698
01:44:08,840 --> 01:44:14,770
'Well that's good, because the islanders wouldn't
be too happy about outsiders moving in.

1699
01:44:14,770 --> 01:44:19,489
It'd take about twenty years before you were
accepted.'

1700
01:44:19,489 --> 01:44:21,920
Tristan sat there for a few minutes.

1701
01:44:21,920 --> 01:44:24,929
Being in Anna's company again that day had
affected him.

1702
01:44:24,929 --> 01:44:31,340
He remembered last night - the taste of her
lips, the smell of her perfume.

1703
01:44:31,340 --> 01:44:33,860
He turned to look at them both and said,

1704
01:44:33,860 --> 01:44:40,270
'Now, if you really want to live down here
how about buying Dolphin Cottage?'

1705
01:44:40,270 --> 01:44:42,150
'Are you serious?'

1706
01:44:42,150 --> 01:44:43,400
asked Stephen.

1707
01:44:43,400 --> 01:44:45,469
'Why do you want to sell?'

1708
01:44:45,469 --> 01:44:50,080
'I'm going to have to buy a new boat for next
year,' said Tristan.

1709
01:44:50,080 --> 01:44:55,409
'This one's OK at the moment, but if I'm serious
about making more of a business out of the

1710
01:44:55,409 --> 01:45:00,080
trips, I really need a better boat - and they
cost a lot.

1711
01:45:00,080 --> 01:45:02,989
Selling the cottage would give me the money
I need.

1712
01:45:02,989 --> 01:45:07,199
But I'm not in any hurry to sell - I just
thought I'd throw it into the conversation

1713
01:45:07,199 --> 01:45:10,780
- give you something to think about!'

1714
01:45:10,780 --> 01:45:13,260
Tristan's face showed nothing of what he really
felt.

1715
01:45:13,260 --> 01:45:19,400
'Wouldn't it be the same - you know, not being
accepted by the locals in Polreath?'

1716
01:45:19,400 --> 01:45:20,680
Anna asked.

1717
01:45:20,680 --> 01:45:26,290
'It would be less of a problem than on Skellig,
because there are already one or two outsiders

1718
01:45:26,290 --> 01:45:28,930
living in the village,' explained Tristan.

1719
01:45:28,930 --> 01:45:32,929
And of course Dolphin Cottage has been a holiday
place for a few years.

1720
01:45:32,929 --> 01:45:38,770
But it's true, we do have to watch it - you
know, make sure the villagers are not pushed

1721
01:45:38,770 --> 01:45:39,770
out.'

1722
01:45:39,770 --> 01:45:44,540
'Hey, wait a minute,' said Stephen with a
smile.

1723
01:45:44,540 --> 01:45:47,469
'This conversation is going too fast.

1724
01:45:47,469 --> 01:45:49,620
We live in London, Anna - remember?

1725
01:45:49,620 --> 01:45:52,449
Your job's there, our friends are there.

1726
01:45:52,449 --> 01:45:55,970
I don't know about my job, but it's there
at the moment.

1727
01:45:55,970 --> 01:46:00,409
I know I said I was ready for a change but
I'm not sure if this is the one I was thinking

1728
01:46:00,409 --> 01:46:02,050
of.'

1729
01:46:02,050 --> 01:46:09,489
Stephen's look to Anna said 'I'm interested
but we need to talk about it together - later.'

1730
01:46:09,489 --> 01:46:14,370
On the journey back, nobody said anything
more about the cottage.

1731
01:46:14,370 --> 01:46:18,950
Anna realised that the possibility of living
in Polreath excited her.

1732
01:46:18,950 --> 01:46:24,050
She started thinking about what work opportunities
there were for nurses down here.

1733
01:46:24,050 --> 01:46:29,610
She also wondered if Tristan really wanted
to sell to anyone or just to them as a way

1734
01:46:29,610 --> 01:46:32,239
of keeping in touch with her.

1735
01:46:32,239 --> 01:46:37,369
Maybe it was asking for trouble even to think
about it.

1736
01:46:37,369 --> 01:46:41,280
A wonderful holiday or a new way of life?

1737
01:46:41,280 --> 01:46:43,900
That was on their minds for the next few days.

1738
01:46:43,900 --> 01:46:49,869
For Stephen and Anna there were days when
they seemed to do nothing except eat, sleep,

1739
01:46:49,869 --> 01:46:52,520
read and lie in the sun.

1740
01:46:52,520 --> 01:46:57,350
There were other days when they were more
active: Stephen did some more surfing and

1741
01:46:57,350 --> 01:46:58,860
became quite good.

1742
01:46:58,860 --> 01:47:05,270
Anna quietly, without telling anyone, found
out about jobs for nurses in the area - just

1743
01:47:05,270 --> 01:47:07,030
in case.

1744
01:47:07,030 --> 01:47:10,750
The two of them talked about the possibility
of buying the cottage.

1745
01:47:10,750 --> 01:47:16,739
But if they did, would they keep it as a holiday
home or move there to live?

1746
01:47:16,739 --> 01:47:21,060
Stephen told Anna that after the sale of the
company, one of his hopes was that the new

1747
01:47:21,060 --> 01:47:23,460
owners would not want to keep him.

1748
01:47:23,460 --> 01:47:28,650
They couldn't make him leave, so they'd have
to offer him some money and he could then

1749
01:47:28,650 --> 01:47:31,599
use that money to start again.

1750
01:47:31,599 --> 01:47:35,489
The idea of doing something in the Polreath
area attracted him.

1751
01:47:35,489 --> 01:47:39,610
'Can we afford to buy this place?' asked Anna.

1752
01:47:39,610 --> 01:47:44,330
'Yes,' replied Stephen, 'if we sell the flat
in London.'

1753
01:47:44,330 --> 01:47:46,170
'But what about work down here?'

1754
01:47:46,170 --> 01:47:47,460
asked Anna.

1755
01:47:47,460 --> 01:47:50,820
'You'd have to do something, we can't live
off one salary.'

1756
01:47:50,820 --> 01:47:51,889
'I know.

1757
01:47:51,889 --> 01:47:55,119
That's what I've been thinking about.

1758
01:47:55,119 --> 01:47:59,570
I want to see if I could work in advertising
down here.

1759
01:47:59,570 --> 01:48:03,489
I'd even be interested in possibly starting
a small agency of my own.

1760
01:48:03,489 --> 01:48:08,980
Or perhaps I could do something with Tristan
- possibly get a new boat together or something.

1761
01:48:08,980 --> 01:48:11,500
What do you think?'

1762
01:48:11,500 --> 01:48:14,020
Stephen felt quite good about this idea.

1763
01:48:14,020 --> 01:48:20,650
'Find out about the advertising world in this
area first, because that's what you know about,'

1764
01:48:20,650 --> 01:48:21,650
said Anna.

1765
01:48:21,650 --> 01:48:27,739
'But if you meant what do I think about me
and my life, well to be honest I've already

1766
01:48:27,739 --> 01:48:31,139
got some information about nursing around
here.

1767
01:48:31,139 --> 01:48:36,270
There's a hospital about fifty kilometres
away and there's a health centre nearer, in

1768
01:48:36,270 --> 01:48:38,840
Kingham, so I could work from here.'

1769
01:48:38,840 --> 01:48:40,060
'Ah ha!

1770
01:48:40,060 --> 01:48:42,500
You're a quiet one!'

1771
01:48:42,500 --> 01:48:43,500
Stephen said.

1772
01:48:43,500 --> 01:48:46,080
'You never told me you were doing that!

1773
01:48:46,080 --> 01:48:51,630
But seriously, what do you think about leaving
London, and everyone there?'

1774
01:48:51,630 --> 01:48:57,750
'A bit nervous, but definitely interested,'
replied Anna.

1775
01:48:57,750 --> 01:49:01,630
'I think I'm ready for a change, too.'

1776
01:49:01,630 --> 01:49:04,670
She remembered she had thought this on her
last day at work.

1777
01:49:04,670 --> 01:49:09,360
'And this place has become special, hasn't
it?'

1778
01:49:09,360 --> 01:49:13,330
They went on talking like this for the next
few days.

1779
01:49:13,330 --> 01:49:17,970
Tristan didn't ask them anything about their
plans, but they did ask him if he was serious

1780
01:49:17,970 --> 01:49:20,100
about selling Dolphin Cottage.

1781
01:49:20,100 --> 01:49:24,190
'Yes,' he replied, 'but only to the right
people.

1782
01:49:24,190 --> 01:49:30,280
Either a local person or, as I've said before,
you two.'

1783
01:49:30,280 --> 01:49:35,590
In the middle of the last week of their holiday,
they felt they'd reached some sort of decision.

1784
01:49:35,590 --> 01:49:39,469
They'd ask Tristan if they could buy the cottage.

1785
01:49:39,469 --> 01:49:43,949
Other decisions were going to take longer
to make, and even longer to organize, but

1786
01:49:43,949 --> 01:49:46,340
this was a start.

1787
01:49:46,340 --> 01:49:51,820
They met Tristan that evening in the Fisherman's
Arms and told him they wanted to go ahead.

1788
01:49:51,820 --> 01:49:54,310
'Great,' said Tristan.

1789
01:49:54,310 --> 01:49:59,260
He and Stephen shook hands, and Tristan kissed
Anna on the cheek.

1790
01:49:59,260 --> 01:50:05,460
He smelt a little bit of fish, which immediately
reminded her of his car and their evening

1791
01:50:05,460 --> 01:50:06,460
together.

1792
01:50:06,460 --> 01:50:09,910
'Are you going to live in it all the time?'
he asked.

1793
01:50:09,910 --> 01:50:13,969
'Eventually, yes,' said Anna quickly.

1794
01:50:13,969 --> 01:50:15,159
Stephen looked at her in surprise.

1795
01:50:15,159 --> 01:50:20,030
'But we've got a lot of things to do first,
like sell the flat in London and sort out

1796
01:50:20,030 --> 01:50:23,120
our jobs... and things.'

1797
01:50:23,120 --> 01:50:27,639
The three of them said goodbye, promising
to discuss the details the next day.

1798
01:50:27,639 --> 01:50:32,179
'Why did you tell him we were going to live
in it all the time?

1799
01:50:32,179 --> 01:50:35,139
I thought we hadn't really decided that,'
said Stephen.

1800
01:50:35,139 --> 01:50:39,300
'I had the feeling it was the right thing
to say.

1801
01:50:39,300 --> 01:50:42,380
He doesn't really want it to be just a holiday
place.

1802
01:50:42,380 --> 01:50:46,449
I think he feels better about not selling
it to a villager if he knows it's going to

1803
01:50:46,449 --> 01:50:49,409
become someone's home.'

1804
01:50:49,409 --> 01:50:52,429
They walked slowly up to the door of Dolphin
Cottage.

1805
01:50:52,429 --> 01:51:04,389
'In any case, I think we had decided in our
own minds,' she added.

1806
01:51:04,389 --> 01:51:06,219
CHAPTER THIRTEEN

1807
01:51:06,219 --> 01:51:07,280
A visit from Jill

1808
01:51:07,280 --> 01:51:12,310
'I see she's back then.'

1809
01:51:12,310 --> 01:51:16,699
This was the welcome that Anna got when she
went into the shop the next morning.

1810
01:51:16,699 --> 01:51:21,890
'Here we go again,' she thought, 'more gossip.

1811
01:51:21,890 --> 01:51:25,880
Still I'd better try to be polite if we're
going to live here.'

1812
01:51:25,880 --> 01:51:28,449
The woman would be a bad enemy to have.

1813
01:51:28,449 --> 01:51:30,890
'Who's that, Mrs Lennox.

1814
01:51:30,890 --> 01:51:32,570
Who's back?'

1815
01:51:32,570 --> 01:51:34,250
Anna asked.

1816
01:51:34,250 --> 01:51:36,469
'Tristan's friend - Jill.

1817
01:51:36,469 --> 01:51:40,370
I saw her coming down the hill early this
morning.

1818
01:51:40,370 --> 01:51:43,030
Went to his house, she did.'

1819
01:51:43,030 --> 01:51:47,719
Mrs Lennox looked carefully at Anna to see
what she thought of this news.

1820
01:51:47,719 --> 01:51:50,719
Anna tried to show nothing on her face.

1821
01:51:50,719 --> 01:51:52,599
'That's nice.

1822
01:51:52,599 --> 01:51:57,420
I'm sure he'll be pleased to see her,' she
managed to say.

1823
01:51:57,420 --> 01:52:01,969
She then had a quick conversation with Mrs
Lennox about whether to buy brown bread or

1824
01:52:01,969 --> 01:52:06,270
white, and what the weather was going to be
like for the weekend.

1825
01:52:06,270 --> 01:52:12,050
Outside, she decided not to take the direct
way back to the cottage, but to go round the

1826
01:52:12,050 --> 01:52:13,199
harbour.

1827
01:52:13,199 --> 01:52:15,199
She needed to calm down.

1828
01:52:15,199 --> 01:52:18,870
The news of Jill's arrival had shaken her.

1829
01:52:18,870 --> 01:52:23,840
She'd felt over the past week or so that she
could control her feelings for Tristan.

1830
01:52:23,840 --> 01:52:29,960
OK, she liked him, but her feelings for Stephen
were stronger and deeper and she'd really

1831
01:52:29,960 --> 01:52:33,929
felt there wouldn't be any difficulty between
the three of them.

1832
01:52:33,929 --> 01:52:36,590
Now she felt mixed up again.

1833
01:52:36,590 --> 01:52:39,930
All sorts of things were going through her
head.

1834
01:52:39,930 --> 01:52:43,889
Had Tristan known Jill was coming and hadn't
said anything?

1835
01:52:43,889 --> 01:52:45,880
How long was she staying?

1836
01:52:45,880 --> 01:52:47,800
Would she get the chance to meet her?

1837
01:52:47,800 --> 01:52:52,329
Did this make a difference to their plans?

1838
01:52:52,329 --> 01:52:57,770
When she got back, Anna told Stephen what
Mrs Lennox had said, without mentioning her

1839
01:52:57,770 --> 01:52:59,640
own feelings.

1840
01:52:59,640 --> 01:53:04,150
What she did say was 'It'll be interesting
to meet her.'

1841
01:53:04,150 --> 01:53:08,920
'You don't think she wants to move back into
Dolphin Cottage, do you?'

1842
01:53:08,920 --> 01:53:10,760
Stephen said in a worried voice.

1843
01:53:10,760 --> 01:53:12,050
'Oh God!

1844
01:53:12,050 --> 01:53:16,520
This house-buying business is complicated!'

1845
01:53:16,520 --> 01:53:20,080
They sat drinking coffee in silence.

1846
01:53:20,080 --> 01:53:26,070
Down in the harbour they saw Tristan arrive
and with him was a tall woman with short,

1847
01:53:26,070 --> 01:53:27,530
dark hair.

1848
01:53:27,530 --> 01:53:32,700
She was wearing shorts and looking completely
at home.

1849
01:53:32,700 --> 01:53:38,430
Anna and Stephen watched them both get on
board Wave Dancer and Jill, if it was her,

1850
01:53:38,430 --> 01:53:41,600
helped get everyone else on board for the
trip.

1851
01:53:41,600 --> 01:53:46,530
There was no Gary today, only Tristan and
Jill.

1852
01:53:46,530 --> 01:53:51,940
Anna looked through the binoculars at them;
Tristan said something to the woman, who laughed

1853
01:53:51,940 --> 01:53:53,430
happily.

1854
01:53:53,430 --> 01:53:57,389
He didn't look up at the cottage as he usually
did.

1855
01:53:57,389 --> 01:54:02,550
Luckily, Anna had already arranged to go and
look around the main county hospital that

1856
01:54:02,550 --> 01:54:07,369
morning so she didn't have time to think about
things too much.

1857
01:54:07,369 --> 01:54:11,800
She drove there with Stephen who was going
to visit the public library in the town to

1858
01:54:11,800 --> 01:54:16,840
find out what he could about advertising companies
in the area.

1859
01:54:16,840 --> 01:54:21,880
Anna liked the hospital; it was the medical
centre for the whole region so they saw a

1860
01:54:21,880 --> 01:54:24,250
wide range of patients and problems.

